<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Cuts Aid to Egypt from 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt, along with Israel with
which it signed a peace deal in 1979, will get less U.S. aid for
the first time in almost two decades, U.S. ambassador to Egypt
Daniel Kurtzer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference Sunday with Zafer el Beshri,
Egypt's minister of state for planning and international
cooperation, Kurtzer said U.S. assistance to Egypt and Israel will
be "reduced by five percent since 1999."
</P>
<P>
However he denied that his country was planning a zero aid to
Egypt, the first Arab country to achieve peace with the Jewish
state under U.S. brokerage. The two have been awarded U.S.
economic and military aid as "peace dividends."
</P>
<P>
According to Kurtzer, the drop in the annual aid to Egypt from
815 million dollars to 775 million is a move the U.S. Congress is
undertaking in view of skinny U.S. budget resources.
</P>
<P>
The Congress has, however, approved to keep military aid to
Egypt intact.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the U.S. on Sunday signed an agreement on
transferring the sum to Egypt. The transfer will take place as
soon as the Cabinet and People's Assembly ratify the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Beshri said American investments in Egypt are steadily rising,
citing a major stake taken by an American company to the Aswan
Steel Company.
</P>
<P>
Kurtzer said that despite the sizable American investments in
Egypt, the U.S. still wanted to put in more through creating a
legislative atmosphere attractive enough to lure more investors to
come over.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Supply and Trade Ahmad Goweili, who attended the
signing of the agreement, said trade exchange between Egypt and
the U.S. is rising progressively and that over the past eight
months it grew by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Electricity and Energy Maher Abaza said the
electricity sector in Egypt benefited greatly from the 1.7 billion
dollars in U.S. aid to the sector alone, with the result that
about 89 percent of villages and remote areas in Egypt are lit up.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. foreign aid budget has been including 815 million
dollars for Egypt, and 1.2 billion for Israel, in addition to aids
earmarked for international organizations. Cairo also gets 1.3
billion dollars in military aid from Washington every year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the U.S. have hold an array of talks in both Cairo
and Washington since July on establishing a new system of
cooperation that puts emphasis on enhancing economic and trade
ties and rescheduling the aid program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
