<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A World Bank delegation will proceed to Egypt later
this month to discuss with Egyptian officials ways of expending a
300 million-dollar-loan the Bank has agreed to provide this current
year to help modernize Egyptian health facilities.
</P>
<P>
According to Sunday's Arabic daily Al Hayat, Egyptian Minister
of Health Ismail Sallam signed the loan agreement with the World
Bank in May.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a Bank official as saying that the mission
which will comprise experts in the fields of health and social
policies, will help the Egyptian side in defining the ways of
expending the loan and the aspects of modernization in such fields
as hospitals, health insurance and basic welfare.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Arab Investment Company is currently contributing
some 30 million U.S. dollars for seven projects in Jordan, six of
which in the industrial sector, and the seventh in the banking
field, according to a company source. The capital of the bank is
about 412 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Sunday that the company's
capital last year stood at 366 million dollars, as compared to
200 million dollars in 1974 when it was set up.
</P>
<P>
The portfolio of the company's projects include 32 in the
industrial, agricultural and services sectors in 13 Arab states.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Water and Electricity Authority of Abu Dhabi
signed a contract with the American C.M.S. energy company to
expand "Al Tawila" power generation plant to raise its
productivity from 480 megawatt to 710 megawatt by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, which was signed Saturday, the Abu Dhabi
government pledged to purchase the generated energy for a
period of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government has revised its
privatization plan of the Jordan Telecommunication Corporation
(JTC) to market another 9 percent of its shares.
</P>
<P>
This move will increase the total shares available for
non-governmental sector to 49 percent, the semi-official Jordan
Times reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the latest amendment to the privatization plan, the
government said that the 9 percent shares can be sold either
to the JTC's employees on preferential terms or to provident
funds of other state-owned enterprises, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
