<HEADLINE> Greece, Bulgaria, Romania Call for Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Greece, Bulgaria and Romania on
Sunday called for a political solution to the Kosovo crisis in
order to avert the possible military intervention by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration released in Delphi, Greece, after the two-day
tripartite talks between Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis,
Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov and Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu, the leaders stressed that the parties concerned in
Kosovo should come to the negotiating table without preconditions,
in order to achieve a peaceful solution for a large autonomy for
Kosovo within the internationally recognized borders of Yugoslavia
and to respect the rights and freedoms of all the inhabitants of
Kosovo, so that another course of action by NATO be avoided.
</P>
<P>
They said that as immediate neighbors of Yugoslavia, the three
countries were deeply concerned that further negative developments
in Kosovo could have serious consequences for the three countries
and the Balkan region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
As for Albania, the three leaders called on the country's
government and political parties to use political dialogue and
create a state of law, enabling democratic institutions to
operate.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to strengthen cooperation between the three
countries and to encourage contacts on a bilateral and
multilateral level involving other countries in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders agreed to hold regular summits, with the next
session due in Bulgaria at an unspecified date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
