<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Concludes Brief Visit to Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak concluded his brief visit here aimed to defuse tension
between Syria and Turkey, and left for Cairo Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak held talks with his Syrian counterpart Hafez al Assad
immediately after arrival earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
According to a Syrian spokesman, Assad discussed with Mubarak
"the latest developments in the region in the light of the
escalating statements released by the Turkish side over the past
few days."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of sheltering its outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party, which has been fighting since 1984 for an
independent homeland in southeastern Turkey, and threaten to wipe
out Kurdish bases in Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria denied the accusation, and charged that Turkey formed a
military alliance with Israel that does harm to Arab security, and
built a string of dams on the Euphrates River that could reduce
Syria's water supply.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is using his good offices to contain the growing crisis
between Syria and Turkey, and to seek a political solution rather
than military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
He is to meet Turkish President Suleyman Demirel in Ankara to
continue his mediation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is calling for dialogue between Damascus and Ankara, on
the grounds of good neighborliness and understanding, to resolve
their differences.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, who accompanied Mubarak
on the mission, said here Sunday that the region cannot afford
military solutions, which may cause serious problems and grave
consequences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
