<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Religious Team Visits Iran to Better Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 4 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi religious delegation
left here Sunday for a visit to Iran, as part of the effort to
improve relations between the long-time hostile neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Head of the delegation Abdurrazzaq al-Saadi, general secretary
of the Organization of the People's Islamic Conference, said the
visit came at the invitation of an Iranian cultural and Islamic
organization.
</P>
<P>
He said his delegation would discuss means of promoting
relations between his organization and the Iranian side, and will
give a briefing on the adverse impact of the "inequitable
embargo" imposed on Iraq by the U.N. eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will drum up Islamic position to help put an end
to the crippling sanctions, he added.
</P>
<P>
Religious exchanges stopped between Iraq and Iran after the
breakout of their eight-year, protracted war in the 1980s. More
recently they have held a series of talks in an effort to solve
pending issues.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 6,000 prisoners of war (POWs) from both countries were
freed and expatriated last April in the biggest POW swap since
1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq opened its border with Iran last year, and a few months
ago it commissioned a checkpoint complex near the town of
Munthiriya on the border to facilitate exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Iranian pilgrims have been permitted into Iraq to
visit holy Shiite Muslim shrines in the south for the first time
in 18 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
