<HEADLINE> 158 Candidates Approved for Elections of Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's powerful Guardians
Council has approved the qualification of 158 candidates for the
forthcoming elections of the Experts Assembly, the Interior
Ministry announced on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total 396 applicants registered for the elections
on October 23, 49 did not take part in the exam given by the
Guardians Council to decide their qualification and 14 withdrew
their applications, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that it would release on Wednesday the
final list of candidates for the elections of the 86-seat Experts
Assembly, which determines the country's supreme leader.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitution, the Experts Assembly has the
right to choose a supreme leader or a leadership council and to
dismiss the leader if he was not qualified or had some problems.
</P>
<P>
A number of applicants whose qualifications were rejected by the
Guardians Council have applied for reviewing their status and the
council is expected to release the final list of qualified
candidates by Wednesday, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
According to the elections law, the conservative-dominated
Guards Council, whose function is to explain and defend the
country's constitution, is authorized to review the qualifications
of candidates for any elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here regard the forthcoming elections of
the Experts Assembly as the most important one after the
presidential elections in May, last year when President Mohammad
Khatami defeated the conservative candidate Majlis Speaker Ali
Akbar Nateq Nouri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
