<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia Calls for US, French Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-allied South Lebanon
Army (SLA) has called on the United States or France to mediate in
its proposed withdrawal from Jezzine, the country's southern
Christian town, the National Broadcast Network radio reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by SLA's leader Antoine Lahd when he met
with notables coming from Jezzine on Saturday, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
He said he wanted the U.S. or France to mediate between the SLA
and the Beirut government on its pullout from the area under his
announced principles.
</P>
<P>
Jezzine, just north of the Israeli "security zone" in south
Lebanon, has been policed by the SLA since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-styled security zone in 1985 to
allegedly protect its north from cross-border attacks by Lebanese
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Lahd offered to withdraw from Jezzine provided
government troops take over the vacated place and prevent
military groups from entering and using it as a base to attack
the militia or Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government rejected the offer, dismissing it as a
similar manoeuvre made by Israel five months ago.
</P>
<P>
In April, Israeli Cabinet endorsed the 20-year-old United
Nations Resolution 425 but conditioned its implementation on
Lebanese government's negotiated guarantee for Israel's security
in the north.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the offer, saying the resolution asks Israel
to withdraw from Lebanon without any conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Upholds Resolution of Syrian-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa reaffirmed here Sunday the need to resolve the dispute
with Turkey through dialog rather than confrontation and threats.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Syrian and Egyptian newsmen following Sunday's talks
between visiting Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and his
Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad, Sharaa said that threats
were unacceptable and that the Arab stance was in support of
Syria, according to Syrian news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs, Sharaa added, are in favor of resolution of
outstanding issues between Turkey and Syria through cordial
dialog rather than any other means.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have mounted between the two neighboring countries
after Ankara reportedly massed up troops along its borders with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Turkey have been at loggerheads over issues of
separatist Kurds, water-sharing and the Turkish-Israeli
military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of backing the Turkish Kurdish
rebels, who have been fighting since 1984 for more autonomy of the
Kurds in southeastern Turkey and often launched across-border
attacks from their bases in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
And Syria has accused Turkey of forming military alliance with
Israel, saying that it threatens Arab security and undermines
Syria's bargaining position in peace talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa said that "we in Syria are astonished and surprised
about such statements as those recently uttered by Turkish senior
political and military officials."
</P>
<P>
Asked about the repeated Syrian calls for dialog with Turkey,
but had no response on the part of Turkey, Sharaa said that it is
regrettable that there be no reaction to the balanced and rational
Syrian position.
</P>
<P>
He noted that such Turkish stance is the cause of concern to
all Arabs, and "we do not have a pre-conceived attitude toward
Turkey because we are an Islamic neighboring country."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Mubarak's efforts and contacts with
Turkish officials in Turkey will be fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak concluded his brief visit to Syria and left for Cairo
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He is to meet Turkish President Suleyman Demirel in Ankara to
continue his mediation.
</P>
</TEXT>
