<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two MKO Members Killed in Southwestern Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Iranian security forces killed
two members of the outlawed Mujahideen Khalq Organization (MKO) in
southwestern Iran, the Information Ministry announced on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An official with the ministry said the MKO members carrying
revolvers and hand grenades were discovered and killed in an
exchange of fire with the security forces in Ahwaz, capital city
of the southwestern province of Khozestan.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, the two were
identified as Qodrat Baqeri and Nijan Sagvand, both members of a
team from MKO bases inside Iraq.
</P>
<P>
MKO, or Organization of Holy Warriors of the People, was allied
with the Islamic revolution until the overthrow of the Iranian
monarchy in 1979. It then turned against the rule of clergymen and
launched its campaign of bombings and assassinations in an effort
to undermine the Tehran regime.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla group, after being expelled by the French
government in 1986, moved its headquarters to Iraq and staged
military intrusions into western Iran.
</P>
<P>
The IRNA report, however, did not say when the two fugitives
were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
