<HEADLINE> AL Urges Peaceful Solution to Syrian-Turkish Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Sunday urged
both Syria and Turkey to exercise self-restraint and tackle the
cause of growing tension between them within the framework of good
neighborly ties and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Sunday, the league hailed the initiative
launched by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to defuse the
Syrian-Turkish crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak flew to Damascus Sunday morning and will visit Ankara
on Monday in a bid to mediate a peaceful solution instead of
military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reportedly massed troops and armored vehicles along
its border with Syria after stepping up accusations in the past
week that Syria is supporting Turkish Kurdish rebels, which Syria
denied.
</P>
<P>
Syria, on the other hand, blamed Turkey for forming a military
alliance that threats Arab security. It is also infuriated by
Turkey's building of a string of dams on the Euphrates River which
could worsen Syria's already short supply of water.
</P>
<P>
The AL statement voiced hope that Turkey would re-consider its
military cooperation with Israel which "imposes serious negative
impact which started to cast doubt on the security and stability
of the region."
</P>
<P>
The Turkey-Israel military cooperation started in February 1996
with the signing of two agreements, and the two sides have since
carried out cooperation in weapon upgrading, training and rescue.
</P>
<P>
Syria has disputes with Israel over the future of the Golan
Heights, which was captured by the Jewish state in the 1967
Mideast War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
