<HEADLINE> Sudan Lodges Complaint With UN Against Uganda, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
lodged a complaint with U.N. Security Council against Uganda for
its aggression against Sudanese territory, and Eritrea for being
an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press Sunday, Sudanese Undersecretary for
Foreign Affairs Hassan Abdin said Sudan has called upon the
Security Council to undertake its responsibility with regard to
this aggression which he described as flagrant violation of the
U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
He said that Sudan has officially informed the League of Arab
States about the motives and scale of the aggression which he said
constituted a violation of Sudan's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Similar memoranda were addressed to the Organization of African
Unity, the Organisation of Islamic Conference and the Non-Aligned
Movement, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdin said that Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir will also
send letters to African heads of state expounding the motives and
results of the aggression.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has accused Uganda and Eritrea of aiding the Sudanese
rebels, a claim denied by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between Sudanese forces on the one hand, and Ugandan
forces and those of the southern Sudanese rebels on the other,
began on September 14 and are still going east of Equatoria, the
remotest southern Sudanese state. 
</P>
