<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges Yugoslavia to Comply Fully With UN Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Monday urged Belgrade to fully comply with the U.N. Security Council
resolution, calling for an immediate end to the violence in Kosovo
and for early negotiations on a political solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers, at their general affairs council meeting,
agreed that continuing violence in the Yugoslav province only
resulted in the indiscriminate loss of life among the civilian
population, an unending stream of refugees and displaced persons
and the wanton destruction of civilian property.
</P>
<P>
The ministers underlined the importance of the adoption of
U.N. Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 1199 on September 23 and
expected full and immediate compliance.
</P>
<P>
They were also looking forward to the Kosovo report to be
submitted by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and to the earliest
possible consideration of the report by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The ministers condemned those responsible for recent
atrocities in Kosovo and called upon the authorities in Belgrade
to investigate, and identify and punish those responsible immediately.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting welcomed a proposal put forward by the EU's
Austrian presidency that forensic experts be sent to Kosovo to
examine the alleged killings of civilians.
</P>
<P>
An EU expert team will make the trip once the technical details
are taken care of.
</P>
<P>
The ministers stressed the absolute urgency of improving the
humanitarian situation in Kosovo, where there was a problem with
more than 250,000 refugees and displaced people, many dwelling in
makeshift shelters in forests and mountains as winter fast
approaches.
</P>
<P>
The council accused Belgrade of being primarily responsible for
the refugee problem and expressed its determination to further
increase the effectiveness of the existing EU sanctions against
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
It also promised to make the fullest possible contribution to
the international community's pressure on the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia with the exception of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union has already imposed an arms embargo, a
freeze of Yugoslav government-owned assets in EU member states and
a ban on flights to EU airports by Yugoslav national carrier JAT.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
