SINGAPORE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's amended
Immigration
Bill, designed to effectively curb illegal immigration, came into
force Monday with the objective of imposing tougher penalty for
immigration offenses.
</P>
<P>
The bill, passed by the Parliament a month ago, "will enable us
to deal more effectively with the illegal immigration problem,"
Singapore Immigration &AMP; Registration (SI&AMP;R) announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, severer punishment is rendered for attempted
illegal entry and departure, abetment of illegal entry as well as
employment of immigration offenders.
</P>
<P>
The maximum penalty for attempted illegal entry will be six
months' imprisonment and a mandatory minimum of three strokes of
the cane compared with the previous maximum penalty of two years'
imprisonment and a fine of 4,000 Singapore dollars, but no caning.
</P>
<P>
The maximum penalty for attempted illegal departure will be six
months' jail and a fine of 2,000 Singapore dollars compared with
the previous maximum of three months' imprisonment and a fine of
2,000 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Illegal entry abettors will be punished with a mandatory
minimum of three strokes of the cane in addition to the existing
penalty of between six months and two years' jail.
</P>
<P>
The maximum fine for employers (of more than five immigration
offenders) who cannot be caned because they are females or are
more than 50 years old will be increased from 6,000 to 10,000
Singapore dollars in addition to imprisonment of between six
months and two years.
</P>
<P>
Corporate bodies will be fined 100,000 to 200,000 Singapore
dollars for employing immigration offenders, doubling the previous
amount of 50,000 to 100,000 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
The amendments also introduce a presumption clause in the
Immigration Act which will put the onus on a suspected illegal
immigrant to satisfy the court that he was not attempting to enter
Singapore illegally.
</P>
<P>
With the presumption clause, any foreigner found in Singapore
port waters without any valid travel document, or with no visible
means of subsistence will be presumed to be attempting to enter
Singapore illegally.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners found taking precautions at Singapore port waters to
conceal his identity or presence from police or immigration
officers will be treated as offenders attempting to enter
Singapore illegally.
</P>
<P>
the SI&AMP;R also announced that it will continue to conduct raids
and undertake enforcement action to keep the illegal immigration
problem under control.
</P>
<P>
Starting from the beginning of this year, Singapore tightened
measures in a precautionary move to stop inflow of illegal
immigrants and these measures resulted in entry denial of a total
of 60,000 persons largely fleeing economic woes in other countries
in the South and Southeast Asian regions.
</P>
<P>
Government statistics show that the police arrested 3,477
illegal immigrants in the first half of the year, 108 less
compared with the same period last year which had the record peak
figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
