<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Must Compel Israel to Honor Accords: Erekat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians hope that
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will compel the
Israeli side to remain within the limits of signed agreements and
implement them.
</P>
<P>
This was made clear by Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat on Monday in the West Bank town of Jericho in an interview
with the Voice of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said the Palestinian side also wants Albright to obtain
political decisions from Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
to reach agreements on issues being discussed by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to arrive here on Tuesday to push
forward the peace process and to prepare for a tripartite meeting
due to take place in Washington by mid-October among Netanyahu,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that Albright will focus this time with all her power
on obtaining a 'yes' from Netanyahu since it is the only and
shortest way to achieve an agreement before the summit in
Washington," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinian side has already presented to the
Israeli side a list of Palestinian prisoners and asked Israel to
open its prisons and release them.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said Albright will hold two rounds of talks with
Arafat, one is in Jericho Tuesday afternoon and another in Gaza
the following day.
</P>
<P>
Soon after her arrival on Tuesday, Albright will hold talks
with Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Besides the scope of Israeli troops redeployment in the West
Bank, the security cooperation between Israelis and Palestinians
is another key issue hindering the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel wants the Palestinian side to take specific measures to
fight terrorism to ensure Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
Other issues such as the Gaza airport, seaport, safe passage
linking the West Bank and Gaza Strip also remained unsettled.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said he will discuss these issues with Israeli Cabinet
Secretary Danny Naveh on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
