<HEADLINE> U.S. House Panel Begins Debate on Clinton Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House Judiciary
Committee on Monday convened to consider whether to set in motion
a formal impeachment investigation of U.S. President Bill Clinton
for his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
The committee, with a 21-16 Republican majority over Democrats,
is expected to vote later in the day or on Tuesday in favor of
conducting an impeachment investigation, the first against a
president since the Watergate scandal in 1974 and the third in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
The committee meeting was opened by Henry Hyde, its Republican
chairman, who has said he hopes to complete the investigation by
the beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The committee has been deeply divided along party lines since
it received the report on the Lewinsky case from special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr on September 9.
</P>
<P>
A ranking Democrat on the committee, John Conyers of
Michigan, said on Monday morning it was too early to say if the
Democrats would vote for the impeachment hearings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
