<HEADLINE> Vietnamese President to Visit Thailand Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese President Tran Duc
Luong will go to Bangkok Tuesday for a three-day official visit
to Thailand at the invitation of King Bhumibol Adulyadej, it was
announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first Thailand visit by a Vietnamese president
since the two countries established diplomatic relations in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and Thailand signed 13 agreements on trade, investment,
avoidance of double taxation, science and technology, tourism,
culture, visa exemption for bearers of diplomatic and official
passports.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade volume increased to 910 million U.S. dollars in
1997 from 352 million in 1994. It reached 331 million dollars in
the first five months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam exports seafood, mineral ores, coffee, vegetables and
fruit to Thailand and imports motorbikes, paint, tube iron,
electronic appliances and consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has invested in 78 projects in Vietnam with a combined
capital of 1.08 billion U.S. dollars, ranking ninth among the
countries and regions having investment in Vietnam. Thai investors
are involved in mining, food processing, cement production, hotel
construction and fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have gradually solved outstanding problems.
They signed an agreement on delineation of the maritime boundary
in the Gulf of Thailand in August 1997, and reached agreement on
regulations on joint patrols in the adjacent maritime areas, thus
helping put an end to illegal netting operations.
</P>
<P>
To promote bilateral relations, Thailand permitted Vietnamese
nationals to integrate into Thai society since 1992. The
integration process has accelerated since Vietnam joined the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
