<HEADLINE> China Has long been Striving for Realizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- "To realize human
rights is the aspiration of all humanity. It is also a goal that
the Chinese Government has long been striving for," a senior
Chinese envoy said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, said that "We believe that the universality of human
rights should be respected and it can be even better reflected
once it is combined with the specific conditions of various
countries."
</P>
<P>
Qin made the statement at the signing ceremony of the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. He signed
the Covenant on behalf of the Chinese Government.
</P>
<P>
"As a developing country with a population of 1.2 billion,
China knows all too well the importance of the right to
subsistence and the right to development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people's livelihood has been greatly improved, he
said, "This, to a large extent, promoted the realization of their
economic, social and cultural rights."
</P>
<P>
"As a socialist country under the rule of law, China attaches
equal importance to individual human rights," he said, "It
respects and protects civil and political rights and opposes any
acts that violate a citizen's legitimate rights."
</P>
<P>
Ever since 1978, Chinese legislature has promulgated over 300
laws and law-related decisions, he said, adding that a relatively
complete legal system for the protection of human rights has taken
shape.
</P>
<P>
"All the tremendous progress China has made so far has laid the
solid foundation for China to sign or accede to more international
human rights instruments," he added.
</P>
<P>
On September 23, Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, in his
speech to the 53rd General Assembly session, declared that China
would sign the Covenant in early October.
</P>
<P>
The Covenant was adopted by the General Assembly and opened for
signature in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
