<HEADLINE> Georgia Seeks Closer Ties with Russia, NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze on Monday moved to reassure Russia over Georgia's
links with NATO, saying both countries had strategic common
interests.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency quoted the president as saying that he
welcomed the selection of Yevgeny Primakov as the new Russian
prime minister and stressing that Russia's internal stability had
a great influence on Georgia and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana's visit last
week, he said Georgia was developing its ties with the alliance to
promote its integration into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said it was believed to be the first time the
president had announced his country's willingness to develop ties
with NATO.
</P>
<P>
The growing cooperation could also spell the revival of
scientific departments which made great contributions to the
country's military and civilian industries during the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
The president confirmed he and Solana discussed stronger
military links and held similar views on many international and
regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Georgian-Russian ties could be improved, said Shevardnadze, but
he added, "The sooner the conflict in Abkhazia is settled, the
faster the relations between the two countries will develop in
political, economic, spiritual and other fields."
</P>
<P>
A military conflict broke out in 1992 when Abkhazia, an
autonomous republic of Georgia, declared itself a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Shevardnadze and the Abkhazian leadership,
Russian peacekeeping troops entered Abkhazia in mid-1994. Under
the mediation of Russia and the U.N., a ceasefire was reached in
the same year. However, the final status of Abkhazia has yet to be
decided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
