<HEADLINE> Kosovo Crisis Not Changed: NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The NATO allies said on Monday
that the Kosovo crisis had not been eased as had been expected
after the adoption of the United Nations Security Council
Resolution 1199.
</P>
<P>
Veteran United States envoy to the Balkans Richard Holbrooke
quoted NATO Secretary General Javier Solana as saying that the
situation in the Yugoslav province "remained fully as serious
today as it was a week or two ago".
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke briefed NATO allies during a stopover before going on
to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance was expecting a situation
clarification report to be delivered by the United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan on Monday and due to be considered by
the Security Council later in the week.
</P>
<P>
Some NATO allies argued that a U.N. finding that the Yugoslav
authorities were defying the UNSCR 1199 adopted on September 23
calling for an immediate cease of violence in Kosovo would give
them the legal basis for "further measures" to enforce the demands
put forward by the resolution.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been trying to get a U.N. mandate as the legal basis
for its planned military intervention in the Yugoslav province in
the form of air strikes or deployment of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers agreed in May to authorize the military
arm of the 16-nation alliance to study the options that can be
used in the event of a military intervention.
</P>
<P>
NATO conducted an air-borne exercise in neighboring Albania on
June 18, immediately after its defense ministers met in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The alliance activated its action warning on September 24 for
initiating the air strikes after the United Nations adopted the
1199 resolution and the action warning would pave the way for the
eventual intervention.
</P>
<P>
But Russia has warned repeatedly that it would veto any U.N.
resolution that would otherwise authorize the use of force by
outside forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Duma, the lower house of the parliament, said last
week that any intervention by NATO would be viewed as "unlawful
aggression".
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke told the press that Solana and NATO European allied
supreme commander General Wesley Clark told him that "significant
military forces, regular forces and military uniformed police
remain in Kosovo" despite the fact that Belgrade insisted that its
offensive was over and its troops were pulling out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
