<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Promoting Sino-British Astronomical Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain and China will hold a
series of exhibitions, question and answer sessions, symposiums,
and other activities over the next few months to promote astronomy
in the two countries, according to Anthony Sprake, an envoy at the
British Embassy in China.
</P>
<P>
The photo exhibition, "shooting stars", will be held in Beijing
through January of next year. Sprake said that that the photos
were shot by the British photographer David Malin, and will help
scientists and professionals as well as amateurs, especially young
people, appreciate and understand astronomy better.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and British have already been working together to
develop education materials and practical activities for young
people to observe the Leonid meteor shower, he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Meteorological Association said that China is the
best place to see the Leonid meteor shower, which is connected to
the Temple-Tuttle comet, on November 18.
</P>
<P>
Sprake said that astronomy contests are being organized in
China and the UK and British winners will come to China to see the
November meteor shower, while Chinese winners will go to the UK
next year to see an eclipse.
</P>
<P>
Some British scientists and their Chinese counterparts will
attend a symposium on astronomy and popular science in Beijing
this month.
</P>
<P>
David Malin has invented ways of extracting further information
from astronomical photos that has brought him international
fame. A new technique led to the discovery of an extremely faint
but massive galaxy in 1987 that was then named Malin-1.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is sponsored by Beijing's Ancient Observatory
and the Cultural and Education Section of the British Embassy in
China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Cooperative Law Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, Octorber 5 (Xinhua) -- The Li Guoji Law Office, in
the Heping Hotel on Shanghai's Bund, is only one of 400-some law
offices in Shanghai, but it is a milestone in the Chinese legal
system.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Li Guoji opened the first cooperative law office on
the Chinese mainland, focusing on economic law. The firm is now a
legal adviser for more than 400 foreign and domestic companies,
including some big ones like Matsushita Electric Works, Ltd. and
Mitsubishi Electric Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Li was one among the first group of lawyers in China after 1949
and has witnessed many improvements in China's legal system. He
became a judge after graduation from Fudan University in
1952. When China reinstituted a lawyer system 4 years later, he
volunteered to go from being a judge to being a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
In 1957, he became famous overnight when he acted as defense
lawyer in a prominent case, but was labeled as a "Rightist" not
long afterwards and was sent to do manual labor in the countryside
for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, he returned to the Shanghai Higher People's Court and
became the first lawyer to resume work in China after the
"Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976). His elegant appearance and
eloquent speeches impressed audiences a great deal. The Japanese
consulate in Shanghai sent a copy of a TV program about him to
Japan with the title "Lawyers Reappear in China."
</P>
<P>
Li himself says, "My fate is tied to China's future. Since
China began the reforms and opening up in 1978, people have craved
democracy and a legal system and our lawyers have found plenty of
ways to serve the common folk." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
