<HEADLINE> U.S. House Panel Begins Considering Impeachment Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House Judiciary
Committee convened Monday to consider whether there is enough
evidence to open an impeachment inquiry against President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The panel began in closed session and then planned to open it
to the public for brief statements by all members and a summation
of the evidence by majority and minority counsel.
</P>
<P>
With the Republican majority on the panel supporting a
resolution to move ahead with the inquiry, the Democrats have
little chance to shape the outcome.
</P>
<P>
The hearing ends the review of evidence submitted by
Independent Council Cenneth Starr. It opens a path to an
impeachment inquiry that will enter the history books, along with
Watergate and the impeachment case against post-Civil War
President Andrew Johnson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
