<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Folk Dance Kicks Off HK Mid-Autumn Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A large scale song and dance
parade performed by 40 artists from northeast China's Heilongjiang
province raised the curtain of the annual Mid-Autumn Lantern
Carnival in Victoria Park here.
</P>
<P>
The traditional annual carnival is organized by the Provisional
Urban Council (PUC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR).
</P>
<P>
The performances by the Heilongjiang Performing Troupe featured
superb skills with a flavor and distinctive style of the
area. Many of the artists and programs had won arts and cultural
prizes at provincial and national level in China.
</P>
<P>
The Carnival's opening ceremony was officiated at by
Vice-Chairman of the PUC Ip Kwok-chung, Chairman of the Council's
Entertainment Select Committee Christina Ting Yuk-chee and
Director of Urban Services Elaine Chung Lai-kwok.
</P>
<P>
Apart from artistic performances from Heilongjiang, there were
also performances by local performing groups such as the Hong Kong
Chinese Orchestra, the Hong Kong Dance Company and the Hong Kong
Ching's Magic and Acrobatic on Chinese music, traditional dance,
acrobatics and magic etc.
</P>
<P>
Both local residents and overseas visitors were attracted to
the lantern show. Highlighting the show was a six-meter gorgeous
lantern named "Dragon and Phoenix Chasing the Moon" made in
Guangzhou, south China, which was surrounded by admirers and
photo-takers.
</P>
<P>
The Lantern Corridor Exhibition in the Park was also crowded
with people appreciating the exquisite designs by craftsmen from
Chinese cities of Guangzhou, Quanzhou and Foshan and local
craftsmen on themes such as birds, insects and the 12 Chinese
traditional zodiac signs.
</P>
<P>
Another lantern carnival at Ko Shan Road Park, Kowloon, was as
well attractive. Apart from the splendid five-meter "Joyful
Children in the Moonlight" lantern, a program named "Cantonese
Opera and Chinese Instrumental Concert" was also staged at the Ko
Shan theater with East New Territories Youth Chinese Orchestra of
the Music Office performing a wide range of melodious Chinese
music for the audience.
</P>
<P>
Children were taken care of and were provided with educational
and amusing activities in the "Children's Fun Corner" at both
venues which helped publicize and remind them to keep the
environment clean.
</P>
<P>
Among other festival-related activities organized or financed
by the PUC were an annual lantern design competition, a lantern
exhibition and 29 district carnivals organized by local community
in the nine urban districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
