<HEADLINE> Third Islamic Court Set Up in South Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A Islamic Sharia court was
inaugurated here Monday, bring the total number in south
Mogadishu to three.
</P>
<P>
All roads leading to the court was blocked by heavily armed
militiamen, many of whom wore beards and black coats, and dozens
of battle wagons including double barrel anti-aircraft heavy
machine guns.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic court sponsored by the Byr subclan of Habar Gidir,
the largest in number among the subclans of Habar Gidir of
Hussein Mohamed Aidid, had had its inauguration postponed many
times.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony was attended by thousands of people
cheering for the restoration of the law and prestigious Muslim
scholars.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Aden Abdulle Weyrah, one of the Islamic judges of the
new court, disclosed on the occasion that their first objective
is to eradicate the illegal roadblocks stretched along the
Mogadishu-Afgoie road.
</P>
<P>
Abdullahi Dhimbil, chairman of the Heavy Duty Transportation
Committee, said the vehicles' owners were the worst victims of
the roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
He said his committee which represents 1,800 lorries are ready
to donate more than 3,000 assault rifles and money to encourage
the Islamic court for the restoration of smooth traffic on all
the roads especially the one linking the capital to the southern
regions which was seriously hampered by the illegal roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Moallim Hassan, the well respected Islamic leader of
Mogadishu, also told the people not to support any kind of rule
unless it is based on Islam according to the Muslim religion.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Mogadishu are only now getting close to
deviating themselves from the road of Satan," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is believed this court will be the strongest if it operates
effectively and will more likely unite the other courts in
restoring the rule of law especially in south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the recently announced disputed administration
of Mogadishu including Ugas Ali Mohamed Ali, a deputy governor of
Mogadishu, and Hassan Abdulle Qalad from the Supreme Council of
Mogadishu were among the officials who also addressed the people
on how their administration supports the Islam and its
application in restoration law and order to the chaotic capital
of Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
