<HEADLINE> Pak-Indian Foreign Secretaries to Meet on Oct. 16-17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The foreign secretaries of
Pakistan and India will engage in important talks here on October
16 and 17 to try to settle the outstanding disputes, including
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Associated Press of Pakistan
Monday, Indian Foreign Secretary K. Raghunath will arrive in
Islamabad on October 15. Formal talks will begin the next day,
after a one-year deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted official sources as saying another round of
dialogue will take place in New Delhi in the first week of
November.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian counterpart Atal
Behari Vajpayee during their recent meeting in New York had agreed
to resume dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers have directed their foreign secretaries
to discuss initially an eight-point agenda. It includes Kashmir,
Siachen, Wuller Barrage, Sir Creek, peace and security including
confidence building measures, terrorism and drug trafficking,
economic and commercial cooperation and promotion of friendly
exchange in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also agreed on operationalizing
mechanism to address all items in the agenda of June 23, 1997 in a
peaceful and composite manner.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Siddique Kanju, while
apprising the National Assembly of Islamabad's stand on the
Kashmir dispute Monday, expected "a forward movement" on the
settlement of the issue that remains underlying cause of tension
for the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"We have repeatedly emphasized the centrality of the Jammu and
Kashmir issue to Pakistan-India relations. Without progress on
this core issue there cannot be any tangible movement in other
areas of bilateral relationship," he added.
</P>
<P>
He assured the parliament that the dialogue will take place on
the basis of 1997 Islamabad Agreement which puts issues of Kashmir
and peace and security on top of the eight-item agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
