<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Airline to Cease Chartered Flights in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's flagship airline,
Cathay Pacific Airways, will end its domestic chartered flights in
the Philippines Wednesday, the airline said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific announced the decision Monday after receiving
confirmation that Philippine Airlines, the country's leading
carrier, will resume its services this week.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong airline was asked to provide chartered domestic
services in the Philippines to fill the void left over by the
closure of the Philippine Airlines in late September.
</P>
<P>
When Cathay Pacific ceases its temporary operation Wednesday,
it will have provided a total of 60 chartered flights, linking key
cities in the Philippines. The last flight will leave Cebu for
Manila Wednesday evening, ten days after the Hong Kong airline
began offering services within the Southeast Asian country.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to be able to respond to President Estrada's
request to help the Philippines maintain aviation services in a
difficult time," said Philip Chen, Cathay Pacific's chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines suspended its half-century operation on
September 23 after negotiations collapsed between the management
and the trade union on a recovery plan for the airline. It used to
handle about 80 percent of domestic flights and about 55 percent
of all passenger traffic in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific currently operates 38 international round-trip
flights a week between Hong Kong and the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
