<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Symposium On Iodine Deficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- An international symposium on
eliminating iodine deficiency disorders by the year 2000 opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing said that he is asking
government departments to increase preventive measures to lay a
solid foundation for the work, which is significant in improving
the health of Chinese and the global eradication of the disorder.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, the then Chinese Premier Li Peng committed China to
eliminating the disorder by 2000 when he signed the "World
Declaration for the Survival, Protection and Development of
Children". Since then, iodized salt has become an effective and
easy way to stop the disorder.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization estimates there are more than 400
million Chinese living in areas with the iodine deficiency,
accounting for 40 percent of victims in the world.
</P>
<P>
Iodine deficiency can result in low levels of intelligence in
infants, children, and adolescents.
</P>
<P>
There are about six million babies born in iodine deficient
areas in China annually, who are believed to run the risk of
suffering from the disorder if it is not tackled soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU: Ministerial Accession Negotiation Set for November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
on Monday that its enlargement process would enter a crucial phase
next month when accession negotiations rise to ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel said that the
general affairs council meeting of EU foreign ministers agreed the
enlargement process should get substantive by November.
</P>
<P>
The council demanded that progress reports on the six applicant
countries already in accession talks be submitted for assessment
and approval as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel, whose country holds the rotating presidency of the
15-nation EU, said the ministerial accession negotiations, due to
start on November 10, would be "really substantial."
</P>
<P>
There would be no ceremonial elements in the negotiations in
which seven of the 11 sets of accession requirements will be
discussed, said Schuessel.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Romania, Slovenia and
Cyprus have each received 11 sets of accession requirements
ranging from infrastructure to democratization.
</P>
<P>
When asked if some of the easier-to-meet requirements could be
bypassed in the November negotiation, Schuessel said it was the
accession norm that no requirements be bypassed before the final
package could be made for enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Formal accession talks with the six countries began in March
this year.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia and Turkey are also
applying for EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
