<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Calls on Armed Forces to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Monday called on the Armed Forces (ABRI) to continue
fighting for the nation, and also anticipating the growth of
dangerous tendencies in society.
</P>
<P>
"The ABRI should maintain its role as a power the people could
rely on to solve the country's security problems," Habibie said
during the ABRI's 53rd anniversary celebration here.
</P>
<P>
To maintain this role, he said, the ABRI needs to change its
vision, mission, policies and strategies and to carry out its
duties, and it needs to be professional, effective, efficient and
modern.
</P>
<P>
"Only through these could the ABRI contribute its best to the
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the dangerous tendencies growing in society, Habibie said,
"Such radical movements, which claim to be reform movements, are
slowly coming to the fore. Some leaders of these radical movements
have been planning to stage mass actions."
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the National Front, established on August 6,
agreed to mobilize the masses within 40 days in an effort to make
Habibie resign. The front, an association of retired generals and
officials, is led by prominent figures such as Lt. Gen. (ret.)
Kemal Idris, and has, since its inception, declared itself to be a
moral force and in opposition to Habibie.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Indonesian politicians, religious leaders
and observers expressed alarm at the weekend over the stated
support of the National Front for student activists' campaign to
force Habibie to resign.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after attending a ceremony marking the
ABRI's 53rd anniversary here Monday, ABRI Commander Gen. Wiranto
said the ABRI will take firm measures based on existing laws
against those who try or intend to frustrate the implementation of
the national agenda, including the holding of an extraordinary
session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) and general
elections.
</P>
<P>
He said the ABRI would be compelled to deal resolutely with
trouble-makers and rabble-rousers to protect the majority of the
more than 200 million Indonesian people.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the warning was directed at a group of retired
military officers, Wiranto said there were no accusations because
the most important thing now was how to conduct investigations and
examinations to arrive at conclusions about who they were.
</P>
<P>
Anyone, to whichever group he or she belonged, will be dealt
with firmly if he or she planned to frustrate the national agenda,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
