<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Falls on key Asian markets
triggered a weakening of Australian shares Monday, with trends
exaggerated by lower than usual volumes.
</P>
<P>
In the first day of trading after the Australian Liberal Party
and National Party coalition victory in the Australian federal
election, the all ordinaries index finished 16.6 points lower at
2,515.7, with a holiday in New South Wales state and some other
states resulting in volume levels being cut by about one third.
</P>
<P>
The local market opened stronger following Friday's rally on
Wall Street, but drops in the Japanese and Hong Kong markets meant
that soon gave way to negative sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The federal poll had little impact on trading on the bourse
overall, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 35 points to 4,390.7, with the
banking sector lower by a similar quantum to the broader market.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank fell 24 cents to 19.44 Australian
dollars, Westpac bank dropped 2.8 cents to 9.01 Australian dollars
while Commonwealth Bank of Australia lost 42.3 cents to 18.495
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bucking the trend of the majors was ANZ bank, which rose seven
cents to 8.65 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished 0.6 points lower at 1,008.9,
with falls in diversified majors offsetting a strong rise in gold
stocks.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP was down 10 cents at 11.70 Australian
dollars, global miner Rio Tinto fell 26.7 cents to 19.533
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index soared 48.8 points to 1,244.6 as the bullion
price added to its strength, improving 10 U.S. cents to 299.40
U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 163.33 million shares at a value of 402.79 million
Australian dollars, with 395 falls, 373 rises and 326 steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
