leaders there," a senior Taliban representative based in Islamabad
said last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi said that it has not yet been decided as to whether or
not the U.N. envoy will visit other regional countries. Brahimi
will stay in Islamabad till he feels it necessary for his mission,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that Taliban official for foreign affairs Abdul
Jalil, who visited Islamabad last week, discussed with the
Pakistani side matters relating to Brahimi's visit. However, no
official information was available about Jalil's activities in
Pakistan. 
