<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sub-Saharan Africa Marginalized from Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- "The World Development
Report 1998/99" issued by the World Bank Monday indicated that
Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) has generally been marginalized from the
telecommunication revolution.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, SSA had about 1.46 million working phone lines
serving a population of about 575 million, excluding South Africa
(with four million lines), said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the annual report noted that there has been a gradual
wave of reform in telecommunication in the SSA over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 75 percent telephone lines in SSA are "private''
today, though the bulk of these are in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The report said ten countries, including Ghana, Senegal,
Uganda, Guinea, Cote D'ivoire and South Africa have privatized
national operators and 15 more countries, including Madagascar,
Cameroon, Tanzania and Malawi, intend to do so.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the proceeds of privatization amount to
approximately 1.7 billion U.S. Dollars with roll-out obligations
by companies of 3.8 million lines (4-6 billion U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Investment costs have decreased from 5,000 to 1,000 Dollars
per line. There has also been increasing choice with regard to
equipment, interconnection and international transmission
capacity. The cellular market, almost completely private,
comprises about 20 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
Though the Internet is growing quickly, access remains
limited, the report added, saying the opportunities for the
private sector during this liberalization phase are substantial,
especially with regard to cellular telephones, paging, voice-mail
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, new communications technologies
(especially wireless and satellite) could accelerate SSA's
economic growth and poverty alleviation. Timely access to local
and international agricultural commodity price information, for
instance, could spur increased production and marketing by rural
farmers.
</P>
<P>
In telecommunications alone, investment totaling at least six
to eight billion Dollars would be required in SSA (excluding
South Africa) over the next four years to add an additional 4.5
million lines so as to achieve a minimum teledensity of one
percent (one line per 100 inhabitants) by 2001.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has been assisting in telecommunication
development in about 25 countries in SSA and is attempting to
establish clear links between its assistance to the sector and
poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
These initiatives include the African Virtual University
(AVU), Economic Toolkit and Workshops for Internet Connectivity
in Africa, the Rural Telecommunications Field Trial and
Commercialization Pilot in Kenya, and the Global Connectivity in
Africa Conference, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
