<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Issues Guidelines for New Forex Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's central bank has issued
a circular providing detailed guidelines for implementing new
rules that force some companies to sell at least 80 percent of
their foreign exchange earnings from current transactions to
banks, the Saigon Times daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The circular specifies that enterprises with government foreign
exchange guarantees must convert at least 80 percent of their
foreign funds in bank accounts into the local currency within 15
days of the money being deposited.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the circular states that non-productive
organizations will be required to sell all of their foreign
exchange holdings.
</P>
<P>
For foreign currency deposits made before September 12, the
deadline for selling the required amount to banks will be October
5.
</P>
<P>
The rules specify that banks are now responsible for
transferring the relevant deductible amounts into temporary
"controlling and holding" accounts pending the forex transaction
15 days later.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, they must immediately inform their clients of
the foreign currency amounts to be sold so that the customers can
prepare paperwork.
</P>
<P>
Banks will be required to make daily reports to the state bank
on their forex transactions worth 50,000 or more following a
decision signed on September 29 by state bank governor Nguyen Tan
Dung. 
</P>
</TEXT>
