<HEADLINE> Mexican Sanchez Hopes to Coach in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's former
international striker Hugo Sanchez said that he is dreaming to
coach in China and hopes to be a truth as earlier as possible.
</P>
<P>
"I want to be a coach as either the Chinese National Team or
one of the best clubs among the China soccer league," the retired
Mexican most prominent footballer told Xinhua on Sunday after a
draw ceremony for the 1999 Confederation Cup in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"I like China and visited the country in August," said
Sanchez, who quit his pro career on May 29, 1997. "I got to know
China's soccer as well as foreign coaches and players working
there."
</P>
<P>
He said China has showed its interest in his coaching
intention.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed as the "Soccer Prince" in Mexico, Sanchez lived up to
his fame in the Mexico World Cup in 1986, when the host team was
one of the quarterfinalists.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez came to the Spanish league in 1981 and made himself a
household name following his move from Athletics Madrid to Real
Madrid in 1985.
</P>
<P>
During his seven-season signing in Real, Sanchez was the five
consecutive top scorer in the league. He also made a record of 38
goals in the 1989-90 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
