<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Inflation Rate Eases Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' inflation rate
slowed down further to 10 percent in September from 10.5 percent
in August and 10.7 percent in July, the National Statistics Office
(NSO) said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The NSO said the inflation rate continued dropping due to the
fall of prices of all other commodity groups except for fuel,
light and water.
</P>
<P>
By commodity group, the rate for fuel, light and water picked
up to 6.8 percent from 5.8 percent in August while those for food,
beverages and tobacco, clothing, housing and repairs, services and
miscellaneous items all plunged, the NSO said.
</P>
<P>
It added that by region, the inflation rate for Metro Manila
went up to 10.8 percent from 10.7 percent in August as the areas
outside Manila registered an average rate of 9.7 percent from
previous month's 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government planned a single-digit inflation
target for the whole year of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
