<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Countries Urged to Strengthen Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries were
urged Monday to strengthen cooperation and reduce duty rates to
increase trade among them.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Jazzman Chikwakwa, Zambian Vice Minister
of Commerce, Trade and Industry during his speech at the fifth
meeting of the Inter-governmental Committee of Experts of the
U.N. Economic Commission for Africa and Sub-regional Development
Center for Southern Africa here in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Chikwakwa said African countries in general and southern
African countries in particular should seriously address and
deliberate on the question of increasing trade among them.
</P>
<P>
In view of the fact that most of Africa's exports are sent to
the European Union market under the Lome Convention duty free
arrangement which will cease in the year 2000, the official noted
Africa's exports will face higher landed costs and "stiff"
competition from mEteloped countries exporting to the same
market.
</P>
<P>
However, for trade among African countries to flourish, it is
important to level the playing field as far as imports and
exports within Africa and the sub-region are concerned, Chikwakwa
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that growth in intra-regional trade can only be
enhanced "if we keep our doors open and reduce effective duty
rates to levels which encourage fair competition."
</P>
<P>
Chikwakwa also laid emphasis on the need of mutual cooperation
to increase trade and develop the region's economies, saying that
through cooperation, trade relations can be strengthened and
trade or non-trade barriers can be reduced.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which started Monday under the theme "Cultivating
Effective Partnership in Southern Africa -- Development is
everybody's business", has attracted over 80 delegates.
</P>
<P>
They came from Malawi, Mozambique, South Africa, Zambia and
Zimbabwe and some Lusaka-based U.N. agencies as well as two main
regional bodies, the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) and the Common Market for Eastern and Southern African
Countries (COMESA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
