<HEADLINE> Manila to Help 29 Workers Detained in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Monday ordered the Department of Foreign Affairs to look
after the welfare of the remaining 29 Filipino workers still
detained in Jordan in connection with Jordan's crackdown on
suspected illegal workers.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing, presidential spokesman Jerry Barican said
Estrada made the order following a report submitted by the
Department of Foreign Affairs that most of the 105 Filipinos
arrested by the Jordanian government have already been released.
</P>
<P>
Barican said that upon presentation of their legal papers and
other pertinent documents, 76 out of the 105 Filipino workers were
released. However, 29 others were still detained in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The president has instructed Philippine Embassy officials in
Amman to extend all possible assistance to the 29 Filipino
workers, Barican said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has a total of six million overseas workers in
at least 100 countries and regions. These workers are expected to
remit some six billion U.S. dollars to the country this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
