<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seeks World Bank's Assistance on New Rail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will seek the assistance
of the World Bank to build a new rail line that will run
east-west across the country, Transport Minister Rear Admiral
Festus Porbeni has said.
</P>
<P>
Porbeni, according to local Daily Times newspaper, said this
in Enugu during a question and answer session with workers of the
eastern district of the Nigeria Railway Corporation (NRC), but
the newspaper did not say when.
</P>
<P>
Porbeni announced in September that the Nigerian government is
considering of building four new railway lines, that is, from
capital Abuja to Kaduna, another from Abuja to Minna, Port
Harcourt to Onne Free Port and the east-west line.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's severed relations with the World Bank has improved
since new leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar took office in June.
</P>
<P>
During a recent assessment visit to Nigeria, World Bank's
Vice-President for Africa, Jean-Louis Sarbib said the bank is
ready for a new partnership with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He identified macro-economic management, poverty elimination,
education, health, energy and transport infrastructure as areas
of priorities which the bank is willing to help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
