<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Not to Levy Anti-Dumping Duties on Unbleached Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- European Union foreign
ministers decided on Monday against levying anti-dumping duties on
unbleached cotton imported from five countries in Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
The general affairs council meeting of the foreign ministers
failed to get the necessary majority to pass the proposal of the
European Commission for anti-dumping duties on imports from China,
Pakistan, Indonesia, India and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, Germany, Britain, Finland, Ireland, Sweden, Austria
and Greece were opposed to anti-dumping duties while Luxembourg
and Belgium abstained.
</P>
<P>
The remaining European Union nations were in favor of the
duties.
</P>
<P>
"It is very good news for the developing countries concerned
and underlines the British commitment to more liberal and fairer
world trade," said British Minister for Europe Joyce Quin.
</P>
<P>
The British government admitted that the decision by the
general affairs council meeting could save tens of thousands of
jobs in Britain alone.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, proposed a 10.9 percent duty on imports of unbleached
cotton from China, 11.1 percent on Pakistan, 13.7 percent on
Indonesia, 16.1 percent on India and 18.5 percent on Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
