<HEADLINE> Malta's EU Membership Bid Re-activated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Monday formally re-activated Malta's application for membership by
acknowledging the receipt of a Maltese letter of intention.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers, meeting in their general affairs council,
unanimously approved the letter addressed by the president of the
council to Maltese Foreign Minister Guido de Marco which
acknowledged the receipt of the renewed bid.
</P>
<P>
The letter also informed the Mediterranean island state of the
council's request to the European Commission to submit to the
council a new assessment report on Malta.
</P>
<P>
The commission gave a positive assessment report in June 1993,
but the country decided to stop the accession process in 1996
after a change of government.
</P>
<P>
Malta reportedly asked to be included in the first wave of EU
enlargement which has started accession talks with Poland,
Hungary, the Czech Republic, Romania, Slovenia and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia and Estonia are also
applying for EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
