<HEADLINE> Lesotho Opposition Proposes Adjournment of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's opposition
parties proposed Monday that talks with the government be
adjourned following claims that South African troops had stormed
the royal palace to flush out opposition supporters, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Southern African Development Community (SADC) commanders
reportedly replaced Botswana troops manning the palace with South
African troops. The opposition protested against the presence of
the South African troops at the palace, saying the troops were
not welcomed because they exacerbated tension.
</P>
<P>
Opposition supporters were at the palace before the bloody
conflict in Lesotho on September 22 to protest against the
results of the May general elections. The opposition claimed the
polls were rigged to prop up the government.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of rival opposition parties and the SADC
delegation arrived at the U.N. house in Maseru Monday for talks
aimed at breaking the political impasse.
</P>
<P>
Among others, the parties planned to discuss whether or not
Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili's government should
remain in power until fresh elections were held in 15 to 18
months.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the government was reportedly firm in its
rejection of the formation of an interim government of national
unity to run the country, while the opposition said it would
accept nothing less. 
</P>
</TEXT>
