<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Three-Party Talks Make No Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's three major
political parties held their second working session here Monday
afternoon to select a National Assembly president and nine
committee chairmen, but made no progress.
</P>
<P>
After more than two hours of talks, the working groups of the
three parties have not reached any agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both the Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and the Funcinpec party
wanted the post of president of the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the Funcinpec and the Sam Rainsy Party (SRP)
also wanted to discuss the controversial seat-allocation formula,
amnesties for resistance generals such as Nhiek Bun Chhay and
Serey Kosal, and a halt to the threat against such opposition
figures as Kem Sokha.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sisovath Sirirath, representative of the Funcinpec, told
reporters after the meeting that the CPP insisted that Chea Sim,
its president, should be the new president of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly session, which is scheduled to meet on
Wednesday, has to be delayed and the new date has not been fixed
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The third working session will be held on October 9 (Friday) to
continue the discussion of top Assembly posts and committee
chairmen positions.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia held the National Assembly election on July 26. The
ruling CPP won 64 seats in the election, followed by the Funcinpec
party with 43 seats and the SRP with 15 seats.
</P>
<P>
Since the CPP does not have a two-third majority necessary for
forming a government alone, it has to form a coalition government
with other parliamentary parties.
</P>
<P>
But both the Funcinpec and the SRP refused to accept any offer
from the CPP. Instead they demanded that an investigation be
conducted into the alleged fraud of the CPP in the election.
</P>
<P>
King Norodom Sihanouk presided over an all-party crisis meeting
on September 22, which ended a three-week protest and brought the
rival parties back to the negotiation table on the formation of a
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The king arrived in Phnom Penh from Siem Reap Monday morning.
It is believed the king's stay in the country will help push the
formation of the new government as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
