<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Cancer Awareness Week for Men Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A major campaign to make men
more aware of the early signs and prevention of cancer got
underway in the European Union (EU), Norway and Iceland on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The slogan of the 1998 Europe Against Cancer Week is "If a
symptom persists, do not wait."
</P>
<P>
European men are advised to see their doctors bodily lumps,
sores which does not heal, a mole which changes in shape, size or
color, or any abnormal bleeding, persistent cough and hoarseness,
a change in bowel or urinary habits or an unexplained weight loss.
</P>
<P>
"Although these symptoms do not necessarily announce serious
illness, they have to be taken seriously as they could be signs of
a cancer that is developing," said Padraig Flynn, European Public
Health Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
He said that cancer could often be detected early if people
were aware of the warning signs.
</P>
<P>
Around 100,000 more men (or 25 percent more) than women die
from cancer each year in Europe, but a recent survey showed that men
are less concerned about early cancer detection or prevention.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 million posters and leaflets will be distributed
this week throughout EU member states, Norway and Iceland to raise
their awareness of early cancer detection and prevention.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU organized a special public information
campaign week last year to raise women's awareness of early cancer
detection and prevention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
