<HEADLINE> Lesotho Multi-Party Talks Resume in Maseru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of rival
Lesotho parties and the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) delegation Monday resumed their second round talks aimed
at breaking the political impasse in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
South African Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamady,
head of the SADC delegation, chaired the meeting, which was
expected to focus on whether or not Lesotho Prime Minister
Pakalitha Mosisili's government should remain in power until
fresh elections are held within 15 to 18 months, South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho government and opposition parties reportedly have
agreed to hold a new general election within one year and half
while sharp differences still remain over many other issues.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Monday talks, the ruling Lesotho Congress for
Democracy (LCD) reiterated that it would not accept a proposal
for the formation of a temporary government of national unity,
while the opposition party alliance said they would accept
nothing less.
</P>
<P>
Unidentified sources were quoted as saying that a handful of
Lesotho opposition supporters carrying anti-South African banners
tried to hold demonstrations outside the United Nations House,
where the talks were being held, but they were soon removed by
the police.
</P>
<P>
The land-locked Lesotho has been in political crisis resulted
from allegations from opposition parties that the May 23 general
election was rigged in favor of the ruling LCD.
</P>
<P>
The SADC troops, consisting of soldiers of South Africa and
Botswana, have been deployed in the capital of Maseru, and
various part of the mountain kingdom for peacekeeping mission at
the invitation of the Mosisili government since September 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
