<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- King of Bhutan Jigme Singye
Wangchuck arrived here Monday on a four-day official visit to
India for boosting bilateral economic and political relations.
</P>
<P>
The visit of his majesty and his discussions with various
Indian leaders would serve to strengthen the long-standing and
close ties of friendship and cooperation between India and Bhutan,
the External Affairs Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, he is scheduled to meet President K. R.
Narayanan, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee as well as other
government and party leaders. The visit would carry forward the
tradition of regular contacts at high levels between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
As soon as Wangchuck arrived here, he met with Indian Home
Minister L. K. Advani and exchanged views on matters of mutual
concern.
</P>
<P>
India has been voicing its serious concern over insurgents
using Bhutan as a training ground for their anti-India operations
in the northeastern areas. Bhutan has time and again said that it
did not support any anti-Indian activities.
</P>
<P>
Bhutan is a small land-locked country and it mainly relies upon
India for providing transit facilities for its import and export
of commodities. 
