<HEADLINE> Feasibility Study for West African Gas Project to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The feasibility study on the
marketability of the West African Gas Pipeline Project has been
completed and the second phase of the study on actual execution
of the project is scheduled to end in February next year.
</P>
<P>
Officials attending a joint meeting of Nigeria, Ghana, Benin
and Togo held last Wednesday in Accra, capital of Ghana, said
they are resolved to eliminate bottlenecks in the implementation
process, The Guardian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fred Ohene-Kena, Ghana's Mines and Energy Minister, and John
Sesay, Director of Transport, Communications and Energy of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), said at the
meeting that they were optimistic the 260-million-U.S. Dollar
project would be completed within three years.
</P>
<P>
The project initiated in 1995 involves the construction of a
600-kilometer pipeline to supply natural gas from Nigeria's oil
fields to the other three ECOWAS member states.
</P>
<P>
Two multi-national oil companies, namely, Shell Petroleum
Development Company and Chevron Nigeria Ltd., are engaged in
financing the project along with the Nigerian Gas Company, a
subsidiary of the Nigerian National Petroleum corporation.
</P>
<P>
Other companies involved in the project include Ghana National
Petroleum Corporation and two others from Benin and Togo. 
</P>
