<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Capital Works Out Plans to Curb Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Dar es Salaam has worked
out a series of measures to curb road accidents, the Regional
Commissioner Yusuf Makamba has said.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of Tanzania will embark on a campaign to
educate pedestrians, cyclists and drivers on traffic rules by
running programs on radio, TV and newspapers, said Makamba, who
is also Chairman of the Dar es Salaam Road Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
Makamba said plans are underway to put into place all road
signs in the city, introduce special training courses for drivers
of heavy-duty vehicles and passenger buses, and to control
reckless driving, local newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
There are also plans to strengthen the Dar es Salaam traffic
police by equipping them with computers for collecting and
storing faster and more accurate data, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Makamba said, the police will exercise
regular checks on road signs, traffic lights and street lamps.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents are among the leading causes of deaths in
Tanzania. During last three years, 5,098 people were killed and
37,624 others were injured in more than 42,000 road accidents in
the east African country, statistics indicated.
</P>
<P>
In Dar es Salaam, more than 2,600 road accidents were recorded
in the first eight months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
