<HEADLINE> India's Communist Party Congress Opens in Calcutta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CALCUTTA, India, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The 16th Congress of the
Communist Party of India (Marxist) (CPI (M)) opened here Monday
with over 600 delegates and representatives from 18 communist and
workers' parties abroad participating.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to review the party's work and
experience in the past three years and formulate a new strategy so
as to strengthen itself and unite all secular and democratic
forces to counter the challenges posed by the ruling Bharatiya
Janata Party (BJP) under the new situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the party's draft political resolution at the
inaugural session, General Secretary Harkishen Singh Surjeet said
that the challenges posed by the BJP cannot be countered unless
all secular and democratic forces come together.
</P>
<P>
In his 90-minute speech, Surjeet criticized the BJP-led
coalition for the nuclear tests conducted in May this year, which
had soured India's relations with its neighbors and isolated India
in the world.
</P>
<P>
The party leader offered issue-based support to Congress party,
the biggest opposition party in the country, for forming an
alternative government at the center.
</P>
<P>
The offer is expected to be debated upon in the week-long party
meeting.
</P>
<P>
In its last congress meeting, the CPI (M) decided to keep an
equal distance from the BJP and the Congress.
</P>
<P>
Surjeet had said that although both the Congress and the BJP,
two national parties, were bourgeoisie and represented same class
interests, the BJP threatened to disrupt the unity of the country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
