<HEADLINE> 1998 HKSAR Progress Report Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has met or is well on
target in meeting 96 percent of the pledges it made in the past
year, a government report said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Progress Report of the SAR government
published Monday, of a total of 961 pledges the government made in
the past year, 922 have either been met or are well on target.
</P>
<P>
There are 39 undertakings, 4 percent of the total, fell behind
the schedule. The report identified clearly those undertakings and
explained the reasons for the shortfalls or delays and promised to
take all possible measures to catch up with these items.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the launch of the 1998 HKSAR Progress Report,
Administrative Secretary Anson Chan said that last year was a
challenging and difficult year for the Civil Service of the SAR as
it was for the community as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"The problems we had to grapple with were unprecedented and
their impact on the well-being of our community was widespread and
 severe," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Taking the "avian flu" for an example, Chan said, it is a new
strain of virus found in the human body and there is no previous
experience to draw on in combating it.
</P>
<P>
"We took decisive actions to prevent the possible outbreak of a
global epidemic," Chan said. At the end of 1997, some one million
chickens were destroyed in Hong Kong to prevent the possible
outbreak of the H5N1 virus.
</P>
<P>
When the Asian financial turmoil first began, no one could have
predicted its magnitude and contagion effects on the world
economy, Chan continued.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has not experienced such a severe economic adjustment
process in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
"In defending our financial and monetary systems we have taken
some controversial decisions, in particular the counter-measures
we carried out in August," she added.
</P>
<P>
In August the SAR government drew on its foreign exchange
reserves to counter-attack the speculators in the stock and
futures markets and enhanced the disciplines on operation of the
stock and futures markets.
</P>
<P>
"We understand of course that there is a price to pay but these
measures were generally endorsed by the community and there is a
growing body of international opinion supporting our move," Chan
noted.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly we have learned from the experiences," Chan said. "We
in the Civil Service have to constantly remind ourselves that we
must always find better ways of doing things," she added.
</P>
<P>
"We must be sympathetic to the plight of the community,
continue to reach out and respond positively to the public's
growing aspiration and sharpen our crisis management skills," she
continued.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, we are committed to an open, transparent and
accountable government," Chan stressed.
</P>
<P>
"It is in this same spirit of openness, transparency and
accountability that we continue to publish the Progress Report
setting out both our achievements and our failures for public
scrutiny," she added.
</P>
<P>
In two days' time, Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa will deliver
his second Policy Address. It is a usual practice in Hong Kong for
the government to publish the Progress Report reviewing the work
in the past year before the delivery of the Policy Address.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Nigerian Leader Receives Party Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Former Nigerian military leader
General Olusegun Obasanjo has received a membership registration
form from one of the political parties in the country but said he
will not fill it for now.
</P>
<P>
The registration form was presented to him Sunday at his
residence in Abeokuta, in southwestern Nigeria, by a delegation
of the People's Democratic Party (PDP) led by Deputy National
Chairman Chief Sunday Afolabi.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, who has been under amounting pressure to contend for
presidency as the new transition to civil rule program under
General Abdulsalam Abubakar unfolds, reportedly described the
situation as an "ambush".
</P>
<P>
He said it was a military common sense that it is safer to
move forward in an ambush than to retreat or stand still,
indicating that he might be willing to yield to the pressure.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said he will not fill the form for now,
because he need more time to reflect.
</P>
<P>
The former leader said he will travel out to the United States
and Scandinavian countries and would give appropriate response on
his return, after due consultations, reflections and mediations.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, who took office as a military leader in 1976, handed
over to elected civilian president Alhaji Shehu Shagari in 1979.
</P>
<P>
He is the only one of the Nigeria's many military leaders who
kept his promise to hand over a civilian regime.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo was released from jail earlier this year by Abubakar.
He was put in jail in 1993 for alleged involvement in a coup plot
to overthrow late military leader General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the form to Obasanjo, the PDP Deputy National
Chairman Afolabi urged Obasanjo to make himself available to lead
the country, especially "at this critical moment of our nation's
history."
</P>
<P>
He said the party was motivated by "our belief that Nigeria
deserves a leader who is a fair player, who can build a bridge of
understanding across all the divides of our national policy and
hence construct a structure of peace for progress on the rubbles
of our past failures." 
</P>
</TEXT>
