<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices End Lower on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Share prices ended lower on
the Singapore Stock Market Monday after the G-7 countries make
commitment to strong economic growth but no joint action.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) lost 16.13 points to
883.86 points.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover was 89.76 million units valued at 119.03
million Singapore dollars (about 70.65 million U.S. dollars).
Decliners outstripped advancers by 148 to 48 while other 226 were
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Asean topped the gainers of the day with a rise of 30 cents to
4.10 U.S. dollars at close. Boustd S moved up 25 cents to 0.95
Singapore dollars. Ayimp edged up ten cents to end at 2.39
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH led the descents of the day with a drop of
80 cents to 12.90 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 lost 30 cents to
finish at 15.00 Singapore dollars. Times Pub shed off 50 cents to
1.93 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the Group of Seven failed to inspire the market
and the outcome of the G-7 meeting could not ease investors' fear
of a global recession.
</P>
<P>
During the week-end G-7 meeting, the world's richest nations
acknowledged the risk of economic contagion sweeping into their
own countries and have stressed their commitment to keep their
economies on a strong growth path. But they made it clear there
was little likelihood of any unified action on their part.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the U.S. proposed that the IMF set up an
emergency lending fund while Japan unveiled a 30 billion U.S.
dollar plan for crisis-hit Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
The dealers remained skeptical if the proposal would work in
the effort for a turnaround in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Needs No Short-term Foreign Investments in Stock Market: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Monday it
would continue to encourage capital inflows, but not the
short-term investment in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
"We will make a distinction between foreign short-term
investment in the stock market and investments in productive
capacities such as manufacturing," Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said when opening the Japan Departmental Stores
Association conference here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Stock market investments are mainly for capital gains and
capital gains are not taxed. Besides, they can easily destroy the
economy by pulling out and taking their money and profits with
them. ...we can do without the dubious benefit of foreign direct
investment in the stock market," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
However, Malaysia welcomes long-term direct foreign investments
in manufacturing as it would help the country's industrialization
program, Mahathir said, assuring foreign investors that they will
gain much by investing in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said that through foreign investments Malaysia had now
become a more affluent society with high-purchasing power and this
had resulted in Malaysia becoming a good market for foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
It has always been the policy of the Malaysian government to
welcome foreign investment, particularly long-term investments
that would benefit both foreign investors and locals, the prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the policy of encouraging foreign investment was
reflected in the continuing keen interest shown by investors in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, a total of 759 projects with a total capital
investment of 7.4 billion U.S. dollars were approved with 44
percent coming mainly from the United States, Japan, Germany and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Out of the applications received, Mahathir said 462 or 61
percent were for new projects while 297 were from existing
investors who proposed to expand and diversify their existing
operations in Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
