<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Get 0.25 Mln Dollars from FAO for Seed Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will get 0.25 million
U.S. dollars from the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) for
emergency supply of vegetable seeds to flood-affected farmers.
</P>
<P>
An agreement in this regard was signed in Dhaka Sunday, said an
FAO statement reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The amount will cover the procurement and distribution of
approximately 25 tons of improved variety of vegetable seeds for
distribution to the most vulnerable flood-affected families.
</P>
<P>
In view of the emergency requirement of the vegetable seeds,
the procurement of the seeds has already been initiated and the
improved variety of vegetable seeds will be ready for distribution
to the flood-hit people on October 10.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide technical advisory services with
the appointment of national consultants for the production of
vegetables under post-flood condition.
</P>
<P>
This emergency assistance project would help the flood-affected
farmers to restore their agricultural production as well as earn
an income, the FAO said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The flooding, which had lasted for ten weeks starting from
mid-July and was the worst ever in a century, had gripped as much
as two-thirds of the country and affected about half of its 127
million people. It also left over 1,000 people dead and caused an
estimated loss of 3.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
