<HEADLINE> Syria Hopes for Peaceful Solution to Row With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Syria hopes that its current
difference with Turkey can be solved through diplomatic channels,
Syrian Vice President Zuhair Masharqa said on Monday in an
interview with an Egyptian radio.
</P>
<P>
Strained ties between Mideast neighbors Syria and Turkey
deteriorated in recent weeks. Turkey condemned Damascus for its
allegedly aiding Kurdish rebels' activities in Turkey, while Syria
bridled at Turkey's growing military links with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey reportedly massed heavy troops along the border with
Syria. But tension eased a bit following announcements of both
sides for a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
"Syria has exerted serious efforts to talk Turkey into
following up a constructive dialog as to find satisfactory
settlement to the bones of contention between the two countries,"
Masharqa said in an interview over the telephone from Damascus
with the Voice of Arabs radio.
</P>
<P>
He said that Egypt and Syria sustain coordination at all times
to serve the interests of the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
"Logic and international law must govern the dialog between the
Syrian and Turkish sides. We hope for a diplomatic solution
especially in view of the mediation efforts (Egyptian) President
Hosni Mubarak is exerting between the two countries," Masharqa
said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made a lightning visit to the Syrian capital and is
expected to make another trip to Ankara to head off the
development of tension into an armed confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Recent tension caused by the "aggressive" statements of the
Turkish military and political officials was among the topics
discussed by Mubarak and Syrian President Hafez al-Assad Sunday,
according to Masharqa.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said on Saturday that
Turkey plans a military exercise along the Syrian border after the
end of current NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organization) exercises
in the area.
</P>
<P>
Turkey also announced plans for fresh naval maneuvers in the
eastern Mediterranean and joint air exercises, which Syria says
directed against itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
