<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of Foreign Workers Apply for Work Permits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of foreign workers have
rushed to labor and immigration departments to legalize their
status in Jordan, since the government began a crackdown on
illegal guest workers last Wednesday, the semi-official Jordan
Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have noticed a large increase in the number of people
showing up at our offices to obtain work permits," Secretary
General of the Ministry of Labor Saleh Tarawneh was quoted as
saying. He refused to disclose the figures in detail.
</P>
<P>
The roundup of hundreds of guest workers, mainly Asians, in
the past days has caused panic among others, who hurried to apply
for work permits to avoid being detained, said Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
Police detained the Asians to check their working status. Those
without valid permits will be prosecuted or deported.
</P>
<P>
As to the illegal Arab workers in the kingdom, the government
will regulate them at a later stage. By doing so, it intends to
give them some time to legalize their status, thus avoiding
possible disputes with the countries they come from.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 to 500,000 guest workers now live in Jordan,
the bulk of whom are from Egypt, Syria and Iraq. Only 40
percent of the total hold valid work permits.
</P>
<P>
The government's effort to regulate the labor market is aimed
at creating jobs for locals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
