<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has said that Egypt will join the nuclear club and retaliate in
kind if it is threatened by Israel, an Arabic-language newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We do not at present think of entering the nuclear club
because we do not want war. War does not solve any difference.
Still peace needs power to protect," he said in an interview with
the mass-circulated "Al-Hayat."
</P>
<P>
"We are not in a hurry (to acquire nuclear arms)...But if the
time comes when we need the nuclear weapon, we would not
hesitate...This is the last thing on our mind," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently ascribing the possibility of Egypt's going
nuclear to the threat from Israel, which is believed to be the
only nuclear power in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"When we talked with the Israelis about this issue before the
(Israeli) present government took over, their view was to open all
files after reaching peace. But (Israeli Prime Minister) Benjamin
Netanyahu is not a man who has fought and does not know what war
means," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader said that it is easy to have access to
nuclear weaponry materials. "India and Pakistan have launched
nuclear blasts. And Iran is said to be on the road. Every country
is ensuring itself a deterrent weapon that can preserve its safety
and protect its entity."
</P>
<P>
Since early 1990s, Mubarak has been calling for freeing the
Middle East from the weapons of mass destruction. In the wake of
the tit-for-tat nuclear tests carried out by India and Pakistan
last May, Mubarak suggested that the weapons of mass destruction
be phased out from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader gave the interview on the occasion marking
the 25th anniversary of the October war, when the Egyptian army
took Israeli forces by surprise and crossed the Suez Canal, which
Israel had held since capturing Egypt's Sinai peninsula in the
1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptians were later pushed back, but Arab's first and
initial victory erased the shame of the 1967 defeat and allowed
Egypt to move toward peace with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Egypt and Israel have been rather cool despite
that Egypt became the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty
with Israel in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
