<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Lower in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Increased fears over the world
economy brought Monday the benchmark Nikkei index of the Tokyo
Stock Exchange below 13,000 for the first time since January 1986.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of those listed at the exchange lost 275.57 points, or
2.08 percent, from last Friday's close to end at 12,948.12.
</P>
<P>
The last time the Nikkei average closed below 13,000 was on
January 30, 1986, when it finished at 12,949.04.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all First Section
issues, dropped 17.33 points, or 1.71 percent, to 996.69, ending
the day below 1,000 for the first time since November 20, 1985.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section was down to an estimated 370
million shares from Friday's 516 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB) was the day's volume
leader.
</P>
<P>
Share prices of export-oriented blue chips plunged in the day,
reflecting the market's concern about possible economic slow-down
in the United States and Europe, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Several high-tech shares marked new lows for the year, due to
uncertainty over the future course of overseas economies.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,337 issues listed on the First Section, losers
exceeded gainers 818 to 319, with 157 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
