<HEADLINE> Intermarriage Can End Ethnic Strife in Burundi: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Vice President Specioza
Kazibwe has suggested intermarriage between the Hutu and Tutsi
for ending the deep-rooted tribal strife in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
She offered this advice when meeting members of the Burundi
women's peace initiative in Mukono, 20 km east of Kampala, over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Monday's Monitor paper quoted the senior official as saying
that this is one of the effective ways of ending this ethnic
problem and saving the country from ethnic bloodletting.
</P>
<P>
She was quick to add that tribes are not really the problem.
</P>
<P>
It is individual greed for power which certain politicians use
to divide people so they may achieve their selfish objectives,
she said, adding that some politicians in Uganda used religion to
achieve the same.
</P>
<P>
The guests were also encouraged to wrest men from power
because she held that it's men who have driven the region into
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
A lot of blood has been shed in the Great Lakes Region and
Africa in general, she said, adding that these wars have been
initiated without consulting women and in the end women suffered
most. 
</P>
</TEXT>
