<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Talks Hit Obstacle: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The second round of talks
on Lesotho's political impasse Monday appears to be headed for a
stalemate as rival parties disagree on who should run the country
before a fresh general election, South African media reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) and opposition
parties agreed Friday that a new election would be held in 15 to
18 months.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties insist that an interim government of
national unity should be installed to govern the country while
the LCD rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Deputy Prime Minister Kelebone Maope said Sunday that
his party would not back down on this issue, according to The
Star newspaper.
</P>
<P>
By calling for an interim coalition government, the opposition
parties were asking the ruling party to effect a coup and his
party was not prepared to do that, he said.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Basotho National Party leader Everestus Sekhonyane
said their demand was based on the understanding that the army
and the police would need to be restructured before new elections
were held. That task could not be left in the hands of one party,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Mamello Morrison, spokeswoman for an alliance of five
opposition parties, said they would insist on an interim
government of national unity at Monday's talks.
</P>
<P>
"We have not lost sight of our fundamental belief that there
is no way one single party can assist the country to move ahead.
We are still going to insist on that position. We hope the other
side will begin to see the validity of this."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the talks could break down over this issue, she said
differing views need not lead to a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties also spoke out strongly against the
proposal that South African and Botswana troops remain in Lesotho
until after the new election.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen quoted opposition spokesmen as warning that
popular feeling against especially the South African contingent
was running high with allegations of harassment of local women by
troops and even of rape abounding.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether order and stability could be maintained if the
troops were withdrawn immediately, she said Lesotho had been
maintaining law and order without them.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, opposition parties slammed Mbeki for his
premature announcement that agreement had been reached on who
would rule the kingdom before the election.
</P>
<P>
The communication division in Mbeki's office described the
gaffe in a statement as "an honest mistake" which had occurred as
a result of faulty communication between his communication
division inside and outside Lesotho. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
