<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Urged to Support Syria in Standoff With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A number of political parties and
local mass media have demanded the Jordanian government to fully
support Syria in its current standoff with Turkey, the
semi-official Jordan Times reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the centrist National Constitutional Party (NCP)
Khaldoun Nasser was quoted by the paper as saying late Sunday that
his party asks the government to take a pro-Syrian stand,
especially when tension amounts.
</P>
<P>
The NCP also calls for the government to work against any
alliances in the region, particularly if they are aimed at an
Arab country, said Nasser, adding that a perceived Turkish-Israeli
military alliance is widely thought as targeting Syria and
standing behind the current Turkish-Syrian crisis.
</P>
<P>
The leftist People's Democratic Party (Hashd) also urged the
government to give Syria unequivocal support.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the Jordanian government to respond to these
(Turkish) threats by announcing its support for its Arab brothers
in Syria and Iraq," the paper quoted a Hashd statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Action Front (IAF), a major opposition party,
echoed the calls of the NCP and the Hashd.
</P>
<P>
IAF Secretary General Abdul Latif Arabiyat told the paper that
the kingdom is duty-bound to support Syria. However, he insisted
on a peaceful solution to the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Renowned newspaper columnist Fahed Fanek late Saturday told
the Al Ra'I, a leading Arabic daily in Jordan, that "we can only
be on the Arab side" and Turkish threats to an Arab country are
"absolutely unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arabic daily Al Arab Al Yawm's Chief Editor Saleh
Qallah said that "we can only stand with Syria if Turkey attacks
it. On this matter, there is no discussion."
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government has so far steered clear of taking
side in the Syrian-Turkish crisis. It called for both sides to
conduct constructive dialog to contain the crisis and find a
proper settlement for their disputes.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom faces difficult situation on this issue, as it has
strained relations with Syria but enjoys close military and
political ties with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's military top officials last week manifested that
their country is in a state of undeclared war with Syria due to
Damascus' alleged support for Kurdish rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
