<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Increase Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- African countries are urged
"to do much more, much faster, to increase their knowledge base,
to invest in educating their people, and take advantage of the
new technologies for acquiring and disseminating knowledge".
</P>
<P>
The call came from "The World Development Report, 1998/99"
with the theme of "knowledge for development", which was released
Monday by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The report warned that "countries that postpone this will fall
behind those that move faster, and the unhappy consequences for
their development will be hard to remedy."
</P>
<P>
The report quoted African ministers, who attended the "African
Telecom '98 Forum" in Johannesburg, South Africa, in May 1998 as
saying that the lack of "policies that promote equitable public
participation in the information society as both producers and
consumers of information and knowledge" makes it difficult for
African countries to share the benefits of the current global
communication revolution.
</P>
<P>
Given that more than 60 percent of the people of Africa live
in rural areas, the ministers identified the development of
telecommunications infrastructure in rural areas as one of the
biggest challenges facing Africa and which deserves priority
treatment.
</P>
<P>
The report noted the remarkable achievement made in the
effective use of knowledge for development as can be seen in west
Africa, where epidemiological and pharmaceutical knowledge made
possible the near total eradication of river blindness.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, over 30 million people are now
protected from infection in 11 countries (Ghana, Burkina Faso,
Cote d'ivoire, Guinea, Togo, Benin, Mali, Niger, Sierra Leone,
Senegal and Guinea Bissau) and 185,000 people have been spared
the disability of blindness. A total of 25 million hectares of
fertile land is now available for settlement and cultivation.
</P>
<P>
In agriculture, the report observed that extension program are
most likely to success if they use existing channels of
information transmission.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey of 676 farmers in seven districts in Kenya
indicated that 39 percent of farmers attributed their awareness
of improved practices to their neighbors and other farmers, and
only 25 percent to extension workers.
</P>
<P>
This year's report focused on the role of knowledge in
advancing economic and social well being, saying "because
knowledge matters, understanding how people and societies acquire
and use knowledge -- and why they sometimes failed to do so -- is
essential to improving people's lives, especially the lives of
the poorest among us."
</P>
<P>
There is large disparity between developed and developing
countries in the capacity to create knowledge, said the report.
This gap still persists and has been growing bigger partly
because developed countries spend more money on research and
development than developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Capital accumulation has long been regarded as the main
determinant of growth. However, the report recognized that
knowledge, not capital, is the key to sustained social and
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
