<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's New Cabinet List Gets Royal Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's new cabinet list
received royal approval Monday, indicating the end of the latest
major cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Some 17 positions of ministers and deputy ministers were
involved in the reshuffle, the first of its kind of the Chuan
Leekpai government since it took power last November.
</P>
<P>
As television station Channel 9 reported Monday, six of the
total 14 ministries of the Thai government will see new faces for
the top positions.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle was characterized by the entry of Chart Pattana
Party (CPP), the third largest political party in Thailand, and
aimed to strengthen the majority of the ruling coalition in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
With CPP's 51 seats in the 389-strong lower house, supporters
of the ruling coalition will hold 257 seats, leading a comfortable
majority over the 132-seat opposition.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government now consists of the Democrat Party,
Chart Pattana Party, Chart Thai Party, Social Action Party,
Solidarity Party, Seritham Party and a 12-MP group defected from
the Prachakorn Thai Party.
</P>
<P>
On the new cabinet list, CPP Leader Korn Dabbaransi will take
the posts of deputy prime minister and minister of public health,
and CPP Secretary-General Suwat Liptapallop, industry minister.
Senior CPP members Prachub Chaiyasain and Sompong Amornviwat will
be minister of university affairs and minister of labor and social
welfare respectively.
</P>
<P>
The posts of education minister and minister of science and
environment went to deputy ministers Panja Keasornthong and Suvit
Khunkitti respectively.
</P>
<P>
The 49-member new cabinet is expected to be sworn into office
later on Monday, and will hold the first cabinet meeting on
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bomb Aid not Enough: Kenyan Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya
Godana has told U.S. officials that a proposed relief worth 50
million U.S.Dollars for Kenya and Tanzania, which suffered bomb
raids aimed at American embassies, is not adequate.
</P>
<P>
The East African weekly reported Monday that Godana conveyed
this message to the U.S. State Department and senators during his
visit to Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
Bombing-related losses in Nairobi alone had been estimated at
500 million Dollars. The 50-million-Dollar relief initiative for
Kenya and Tanzania "does not come anywhere close" to what's
needed, Godana was quoted as saying in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"There is tremendous public expectation in Kenya that
sufficient help will be forthcoming," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, U.S. President Bill Clinton called for emergency aid
to the two east African countries in response to the August 7
bombing which killed more than 250 people and injured about 5,000
others.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. funding proposal is being presented to Congress as
part of a 1.8-billion-Dollar package aimed primarily at improving
security at U.S. embassies and consulates worldwide.
</P>
<P>
About 200 million Dollars of the total sum is earmarked for
construction of new embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam and
for provision of temporary diplomatic services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
