<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Warning to Syria Aimed at Eliminating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's strong warning to Syria
is aimed at nothing but eliminating the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) based in Damascus, local Daily News said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The influential newspaper quoted reliable officials, whose
names were not given, as saying that the Turkish government
regards Syria's support for the PKK as the only stumbling block in
Turkey's final victory against the organization.
</P>
<P>
The official sources' remarks came when Turkey and Syria are
engaged in a war of words over the allegation. In a rising
tension, Turkey reportedly massed heavy troops along the border
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
They said Turkey has cut down the PKK presence in northern Iraq
to a minimum level thanks to the cooperation with Iraq's Kurdistan
Democratic Party (KDP) led by Massoud Barzani.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan and his men
are given shelter by the Syrians, an allegation which has been
denied by Syria.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel said Sunday that Turkey is
sending a warning not only to Syria, but the world because
everybody knows that "Turkey has suffered from separatist
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Over 37,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and the
government troops, have been killed in conflicts since the PKK
started a separatist campaign for autonomy in southeast Turkey
in 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
