<HEADLINE> Sino-German Cooperation Proves Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and German officials and
scientists gathered today in Beijing to celebrate the 20th
anniversary of the Sino-German Protocol on Science and Technology
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Fang Yi and Germany Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher signed the document 20 years ago
shortly after China initiated its reform and opening policies.
</P>
<P>
Extensive cooperation between thousands of scientists and
engineers from the two nations have yielded marked progress in
scientific and technological cooperation over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
German Ambassador Konrad Seitz, acting on behalf of President
Roman Herzog. presented China's Minister of Science and Technology
Zhu Lilan with a Grand Star Cross for her contributions to
ensuring the progress of related efforts. The medal is the highest
prize Germany offers for special contributions in the realm of
politics, economics and scientific and cultural development.
</P>
<P>
Li Xueyong, deputy minister of Science and Technology, said the
two nations have successfully carried out joint programs in
wide-ranging areas, including the energy, raw materials, geology,
aerospace, environment and information technology sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries enjoy compatibility in many fields," said
Li, adding that the two sides have established extensive
cooperative mechanisms based on mutual respect, understanding and
practical attitudes. "Germany is one of China's key partners in
scientific and technological cooperation," according to Li.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Seitz noted that the protocol, the first
intergovernmental document signed by the two countries,
represented "a significant beginning" for beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 people from the two countries attended today's
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
