<HEADLINE> Malaysia Expected to Get 2 Bln US Dollar Aid from Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is expected to
receive 2 billion U.S. dollars from Japan under its 30 billion
dollar aid package to stabilize the battered economies in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"It is in my great concern that Malaysia will get an
appropriate and considerable share of the loans," Japanese
Ambassador to Malaysia Issei Nomura told reporters at the Japan
Department Stores Association conference held here, which was
officiated by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
"We hope we can give 2 billion U.S. dollars to Malaysia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that towards this end, both the government
agencies -- the Economic Planning Unit of the Ministry of Finance
and the Ministry of International Trade and Industry -- were now
in the midst of negotiations pertaining to the yen loans
disbursement.
</P>
<P>
Issei Nomura said that the Japanese government is working hard
for the quick disbursement of the loans.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is one of the five countries that fall under this aid.
The other four are Thailand, the Philippines, Indonesia and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
Of the total figure, 15 billion U.S. dollars will be used to
meet the medium to long-term financial needs to promote economic
recovery in these five countries while the rest would be for
short-term capital requirements. 
</P>
