<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment in Uganda Slashed Due to Insecurity: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- New investments in Uganda have
slashed in the first eight months of this year due to increased
media coverage of rampant insecurity and implementation of new
tax regulations.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether 100 new projects registered during this
period, the first big slump since the country directed its
attention to foreign investors seven years ago, the Nairobi-based
East African weekly paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there has been a month-to-month decline
in the first eight months of this year, with August serving as
the bottom. There were only eight projects registered in the
month.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, a total of 61 projects worth 114.521 million
U.S. Dollars were licensed in July and August of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed this plummet to widespread reports of
rebel activities in the northern and western parts of the
country. It is these reports that have scared the investors
away, it said.
</P>
<P>
Other factors like the new tax regulations are also cited as
leading to the fall. Recently, the Ugandan government scrapped
an unpopular package that offered investors up to six years' tax
holidays.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors are now allowed to pay a 75 percent
depreciation allowance on machinery and plants set up in the
rural areas. The rate decreases to 50 percent if the projects are
in the urban areas.
</P>
<P>
To minimize the influence of reported insecurity on the inflow
of foreign capital, the Uganda Investment Authority has decided
to counter negative publicity about rebel activities by using the
Internet to disseminate information about the government's fresh
security efforts and preferable policies for investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
