<HEADLINE> Experts Discuss Sustainable Agriculture in Asia-Pacific Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- More than a dozen agricultural
experts from countries in the Asia-Pacific Region, including
China, the United States, Japan, India and Australia are in
Beijing, the Chinese capital, to discuss the sustainable
development of agriculture and scientific cooperation in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS)
and the China Association for Science and Technology (CAST) are
jointly sponsoring the three-day Asia-Pacific Conference on
Sustainable Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has focused on environmental protection
throughout the nation's dramatic economic growth cycle, and has
basically succeeded in reversing rapid environmental
deterioration. According to CAST President Zhou Guangzhao, who
also serves as vice chairman of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
However, China continues to face pressing environmental
issues. Heavy summer flooding has mainly been attributed to
abnormal weather, and inappropriate human activities have hindered
sustainable development, according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
He added that China should take the lead in introducing new
modes of production and lifestyles to save valuable resources and
protect the environment.  
