<HEADLINE> 21 Trafficked Children Recovered in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one trafficked children,
aged between five and 15, along with four women were recovered by
police in a hotel here in a pre-dawn swoop on Sunday, press
reports here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police also arrested four persons from the same hotel for their
alleged involvement in attempting to traffic these children and
women to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
All the children and women were inhabitants of the country's
southern district of Cox's Bazar.
</P>
<P>
The four arrested persons belong to an organized gang of
international women and children traffickers who assembled the
women and children at the hotel during the last month by alluring
them with better jobs in Saudi Arabia, police sources were quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The arrested persons told the police that the women and
children were brought from Cox's Bazar to Dhaka by one man and
several others. But the police could not arrest the other
traffickers as they were outside the hotel during the raid. The
case is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
Over 200,000 Bangladeshi women and children have been
trafficked to the Middle East and India in the past 20 years, and
about 20,000 Bangladeshi women are involved in prostitution in
Indian brothels alone, according to reports of human rights
organizations and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government is deeply concerned about the
growing trend in women and children trafficking and has taken a
series of measures in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
