<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Leads in World's Pyrethrum Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenya remains the world's
largest producer of pyrethrum, an environment-friendly raw
material for pesticides, the lastest official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Kenya produces 67 percent of the world's total output,
followed by Tasmania (Australia) with 11 percent, Tanzania 10
percent, Rwanda six percent, Papua New Guinea 2.5 percent,
Ecuador one percent and others 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Output of pyrethrum in this east African country has hit 7,160
tons so far this year, compared with 6,220 tons recorded during
the same 1996/97 period, the East African Standard newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, officials of the Pyrethrum Board of Kenya warned that
the pyrethrum yield is now threatened by the outbreak of root-rot
disease, which has forced farmers to uproot the crop in the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
The disease has devastated the crop mainly in water-logged
areas in southwestern Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urbanization Being Accelerated in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The number of Chinese cities
grew form 193 in 1979 when the country first introduced its reform
and opening policies to 668 by the end of 1997, according to a
report released by the State Statistics Bureau here today.
</P>
<P>
The number of small cities has increased dramatically,
especially on the county level, with eastern areas experiencing
more rapid urbanization than less developed western regions.
</P>
<P>
A number of metropolitan areas have formed around major cities,
including a Bohai Bay area centered on Beijing, Tianjin, Qingdao,
Shenyang and Dalian, another in the Yangtze River Delta around
Shanghai, Nanjing, Hangzhou and Ningbo, and still another in the
Pearl River (Zhujiang) Delta around Guangzhou and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Urban populations continue to grow, with recent statistics
showing that the ratio of urbanites to the nation's total
population hit 17.7 percent by the end of last year, up
dramatically on the eight percent figure for 1978.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative GDP of Chinese cities grew at an average annual
rate of 18 percent between 1988-1996. In addition, the service
industry recorded a 19.3 percent rise in value-added. Thirty-four
cities and prefectures had GDP figures of more than 20 billion
yuan (2.41 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report estimates that China's urbanization level will
surpass 21 percent by the end of the century, with the momentum
for related growth expected to accelerate in the coming century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
