<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gets More Remittances From Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh got about 765 million
U.S. dollars in the first six months of this year in remittances
from Bangladeshi workers employed abroad, The Independent daily
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has fixed a target of sending
202,900 people abroad with jobs this year and in the first eight
months of 1998, 166,466 Bangladeshi people were sent abroad
through official and recognized channels, the report quoted
official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from labor export last year stood at 1.43 billion
dollars. The manpower export is a major foreign exchange earner
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The largest concentration of Bangladeshi nationals, numbering
around 1 million, is now in Saudi Arabia, followed by the United
Arab Emirates with the number of about 270,000.
</P>
<P>
A high-level meeting held in Dhaka Sunday decided to lift a
blanket ban on the export of woman workers, except house maids,
for employment abroad, including to the Middle East, to expand the
country's labor export, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also decided that Bangladeshi workers could not be
sent to Saudi Arabia with a salary less than 300 Saudi riyals,
they added.
</P>
<P>
The government has asked the Ministry of Labor and Employment
to prepare a policy paper on employment abroad, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
