<HEADLINE> Former Malaysian Deputy PM Charged in High Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Former Malaysian Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim was produced before the High Court
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was dismissed as deputy prime minister and finance
minister on September 2, was charged in the Sessions Court here On
September 29 on five counts of corrupt practices and four counts
of unnatural sex and in the Sessions Court in Petaling Jaya near
here the following day on another count of unnatural sex.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's case was transferred to the High Court by judges at the
Sessions Courts after he pleaded not guilty to all the 10 charges
and claimed the trial.
</P>
<P>
At the High Court Monday, Justice Augustin Paul adjourned
proceedings to fix the dates for the hearing.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is alleged to have committed corrupt practices under
Section 2 (1) of the Emergency (Essential Powers) Ordinance which
provides for a jail term not exceeding 14 years or a maximum fine
of 20,000 ringgit (about 5,263 U.S. dollars) or both on
conviction.
</P>
<P>
He is also alleged to have committed sodomy under Section 377B
of the Penal Code which provides for a jail term not exceeding 20
years and whipping on conviction.
</P>
<P>
The situation at the court premises and the vicinity was
normal. However Federal Reserve Unit and General Operations Force
personnel were present.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was arrested on September 20 by police under the
Internal Security Act for calling an illegal assembly here on the
same day, is still under police detention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
