<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder Spree Takes New Twist in Indonesian Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Mysterious killings, targeting
at black magicians and Muslim clerics in Indonesia's East Java
province, took a new twist with the discovery of eight more
victims, the Jakarta Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-three victims have been confirmed in Banyuwangi regency
since August. In September, it was reported that similar killings
took place on Madura, an island off East Java, where a number of
people had been killed.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that eight people have been found dead in
similar circumstances in Jember regency recently.
</P>
<P>
Banyuwangi is a regency 280 kilometers east of East Java's
capital of Surabaya with a population of 1.5 million people. The
regency capital, Banyuwangi, is a coastal town. Jember is about
105 kilometers west of Banyuwangi.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports from Banyuwangi said the targeted victims had
initially been those believed to be "black magic practitioners" as
were the victims in Jember and Madura. However, according to
community leaders, most of the later victims were reportedly
Muslim preachers.
</P>
<P>
Some believe that they are revenge killings while others are
speculating on possible "political motives."
</P>
<P>
Banyuwangi and Jember are predominantly Muslim areas rooted in
the tradition of Nadhlatul Ulama, which is the country's largest
Muslim organization.
</P>
<P>
One military source suggested that the killings were a
deliberate attempt to create tension between Nadhlatul Ulama and
members of the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) led by Megawati
Soekarnoputri, daughter of the country's founding president,
Soekarno.
</P>
<P>
The Megawati-led PDI will hold its congress in Bali this week
and thousands of supporters are expected to make their way to
Banyuwangi port en route to the island resort.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Megawati-led PDI will set up a
coalition with Nadhlatul Ulama to contest next year's general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Head of the regional branch of Nadhlatul Ulama, Kyai Haji
Hasyim Muzadi, said it was obvious that the killers were
well-organized and very professional.
</P>
<P>
"These mysterious people usually come in one to three trucks
each carrying about 40 people who are not locals," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to stop the mysterious wave of grisly murders, police,
troops in armored cars and frightened residents armed with knives
and sharpened sticks patrolled the streets of Banyuwangi on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
East Java Military Commander Maj. Gen. Djoko Subroto had denied
any involvement of his personnel in the murders.
</P>
<P>
East Java police chief Maj. Gen. Moch. Dayat told reporters
that 100 elite Mobile Brigade personnel had been deployed as an
anti-guerrilla force in the affected areas. The police had
arrested 58 suspects, including three thought to have been paying
the killers.
</P>
<P>
"We'll arrest the mastermind eventually (after investigating
these suspects)," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0185 </DOCNO>
