<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Vows to Defend Against NATO Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia Sunday issued a
communique vowing to defend itself against possible NATO (North
Atlantic Treaty Organization) air strikes.
</P>
<P>
"If we are attacked, we shall defend the country by all
available means", the communique, issued at the end of a meeting
of the Yugoslavia's Supreme Defense Council, said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the unanimous stand by the (council) members," it
added.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic Sunday night presided
over the council meeting to discuss the current military and
political situation, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The United States Friday warned that Belgrade would risk NATO
air attacks within two weeks unless it halted fighting, opened
dialogue with Kosovo Albanian leaders and allowed international
aid workers safe access to thousands of refugees in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The communique, however, also stressed that Yugoslavia wanted a
peaceful settlement to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Attending the Sunday council session were the presidents of
Serbia and Montenegro, the federal defense and foreign ministers
and Yugoslav Army Chief of Staff General Momcilo Perisic. 
</P>
