<HEADLINE> Thai Government's Early Poll Plan Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has not
changed its original plan to call an early election before the end
of its term in office, government spokesman Akapol Sorasuchart
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Akapol was quoted Monday by the Bangkok Post as saying a
cabinet reshuffle with the inclusion of the Chart Pattana Party
does not mean that the government intends to fulfill its tenure.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet reshuffle list has been completed and it is
expected to be announced Monday, according to Visanu Kreuangam,
cabinet secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Once the ailing economy has recovered to a certain level and
the Election Commission is ready, an election will be held, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is determined to carry on three major
tasks -- to try to revive the economy, to restructure the
financial, banking and real sectors, and to carry out bureaucratic
reform.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the government has so far managed to restore
economic stability to a certain level and to restore confidence in
the economy in spite of obstruction from external factors.
</P>
<P>
He said restructuring of the financial, banking and real
sectors which has already started would be carried on while the
bureaucratic system would undergo reform to make it more
transparent and more responsive to public aspirations.
</P>
<P>
"The government cannot survive only votes in parliament. It
has to earn the faith and trust of the people," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
