<HEADLINE> Thailand Slashes Aid to Neighboring Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has cut the amount of
aid it gives to neighboring countries for technical assistance by
almost two-thirds because of the economic slump.
</P>
<P>
This year Thailand will give a total 329 million baht (8.44
million U.S. dollars) and next year it will offer 133 million baht
(3.41 million dollars), Monday's Bangkok Post quoted Sumathee
Srisuchart, deputy director general of the Department of Technical
Economic Cooperation (DETEC), as saying.
</P>
<P>
DETEC is looking to third countries to help with funding. "We
are talking to various donors, including Japan and the U.N.
Development Program," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government has already agreed to increase its
donations to 11 training courses for developing countries to 70
percent, up from 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
DETEC will go on financing running projects in neighboring
countries, but will not take on new ones.
</P>
<P>
The Thailand Development Research Institute will advise DETEC
on how to help provide technical assistance during the economic
crisis by handing over a study shortly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
