<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The city of Wuyishan in east
China's Fujian Province recently decided to tear down a three-star
hotel to preserve the uniqueness of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
The city, known for its picturesque Wuyi Mountains, plans to
remove the building from 6,000 square meters of land to return it
to trees and grass as an example of Fujian's environmental
protection program.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's capital, Fuzhou, has spent a large amount of money on
160 hectares of green land and the Provincial Planning Commission
recently canceled a project so that it could protect 32.7 hectares
of mangrove trees.
</P>
<P>
In July, Governor He Guoqiang signed a contract on
environmental protection for the next three years with mayors and
prefectural commissioners of the province's nine cities and
prefectures to get the province's industries that are polluters to
meet state standards by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Fujian has raised 1 billion yuan (120 million U.S. dollars) for
environmental improvement since 1996. In 1997, it improved 488
production lines in 213 factories as part of the move and reduced
discharged waste gas by more than 2,400 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
