<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Biota in Indonesian Sulawesi Faces Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Some Indonesian non-governmental
organizations feared that various marine biota in Central Sulawesi
province will become extinct as many fishermen use explosives and
poisonous chemicals to catch fish, Antara News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of Indonesian Environmental Forum Office in
Central Sulawesi Harli said the bombings have caused damage to
coral reefs and the community of Napolean and Kerapu fish in the
waters of the Togean islands.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the Togean islands is one of the areas in the world
which has the most beautiful coral reefs, including the Atoll
(ring-shaped coral) and the Patch Reef (which stretches along an
unbroken length)," Harli said.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the provincial fishery service Faizal Shahab also
expressed concern about the fish bombings, saying the fishermen's
misconduct would reduce the population of fish.
</P>
<P>
"Not only big fish like Napolean, Kerapu, or even Lobster, but
also small fish will die," he said.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the fish bombings, Shahab said, the fishery
service is cooperating with the Natural Resources Conservation
Board to conduct sea patrols on the islands.
</P>
<P>
However, the patrols have not yet achieved the maximum result
due to limited personnel and supporting facilities, such as
speedboat.
</P>
<P>
He feared that Central Sulawesi's marine potentials will
gradually deplete due to the improper exploitation of marine
biota.
</P>
<P>
Now, local fishermen have difficulties catching Napolean fish
in the 168,443-hectare conservation area, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
