<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Dumping Rules Unavoidable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to impose
anti-dumping regulations on imported chemical fibre products,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Anti-dumping regulations have become unavoidable, since
imported products have severely disordered the domestic chemical
fibre market, said Xu Kunyuan, vice-director of the State Textile
Industry Bureau.
</P>
<P>
China imported 837,000 tons of chemical fibres in the first
half of this year, 37.4 percent of the total domestic
output in the same period, according to the Association of the
Chemical Fibre Industry.
</P>
<P>
Consecutive price cuts by foreign chemical fibre producers --
some selling at less than their production cost -- spurred China's
imports to 1.81 million tons last year, equivalent to 39.1 percent
of the country's total output.
</P>
<P>
China's chemical fibre producers, burdened by pressure from
both the sluggish domestic market and overseas dumping, witnessed
a sharp profit decline and increasing stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
The 118 large and medium-sized chemical fibre companies on
average had stocks of around 135 percent compared with output at
the end of June this year, according to the association.
</P>
<P>
But the key way for the chemical industry to come out of its
difficulties centres on its own adjustment and restructuring,
said Xu.
</P>
<P>
He said that the sector needs to lose no time in upgrading
technologies and equipment and developing new products. He also
urged producers to pay closer attention to applying to patent
their products, rather than simply focusing on production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops New Cancer Diagnostic Method </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese tumor expert Li
Weilian, of the Second Central Hospital of Tianjin, has developed
a new method of diagnosing cancer by observing a patient's tongue,
a method favored in traditional Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
Li found over years of practice that cancer patients' tongues
have similar phenomena that change as the disease progresses and
vary with different types of cancers.
</P>
<P>
Traditional Chinese medicine doctors believe that the tongue
shows symptoms of the body on its texture, fuzziness, and its
bottom that can reflect the state of a patient and the development
of the illness.
</P>
<P>
Li studied 209 cancer cases over the past five years that led
him to the relation between cancers and the tongue.
</P>
<P>
These indices may help increase accuracy in cancer
diagnoses. Effectiveness of mammary cancer treatments has risen
from about 40 percent to more than 70 percent and the method has
recently got approval from a team of medical analysts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
