<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Net International Reserves Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's net international
reserves have declined by 66.5 million U.S. dollars, the Jakarta
Post Monday quoted the central bank weekly report as saying.
</P>
<P>
In its latest weekly report, the central bank said net
international reserves declined from 14.104 billion dollars on
September 23 to 14.038 billion dollars on September 30.
</P>
<P>
The decline was mainly due to interest payment on government
foreign debt and selling of some U.S. dollars for the rupiah to
sterilize liquidity in the wake of greater government spending.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank said the September 30 international
reserves level was still above the International Monetary Fund
adjusted international reserves target of 12.51 billion dollars.
</P>
