<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Downsizes for Peace, Efficiency (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese People's Liberation
Army (PLA) has begun a new move to cut a further half-million
personnel from its ranks over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
China's armed forces reduced their size by one million during
the 1980s. The reduction plan for the second time will be finished
at 2000. By then, China will have reduced the size of its armed
forces by a total of seven million in half a century of its
existence.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that when the current reduction move is
completed, the PLA's personnel, including non-military personnel,
will total 2.5 million, 0.21 percent of the country's
population. In comparison, the United States' army makes up 0.87
percent of its national population, and Russia's, 1.28 percent.
</P>
<P>
An official with the PLA Academy of Military Science says that
China's decision of disarmament has been made "unilaterally,
without any prerequisite or relevance to any other country".
</P>
<P>
Wang Huiqing, a doctor of military science, describes the
disarmament move as "a manifestation and enrichment of China's
outstanding traditional military thinking, which is characterized
by the pursuit of peace."
</P>
<P>
In the last disarmament move, the boundaries of the 11 regional
military commands were redrawn to just seven larger
commands. Infantry forces were reorganized into group armies,
which incorporated most of the previously independent armored
troops, artillery and engineer corps; and new electronic
countermeasure corps and camouflaged units were added to the army
formation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Downsizes for Peace, Efficiency (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's military spending has also been kept at a minimum for
self-defense and demobilized personnel have made outstanding
contributions to the country's social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China's defense budget between 1979 and
1996 was reduced from 5.6 percent to the gross domestic product to
1.04 percent. The 1996 defense budget of 70.227 billion yuan (8.4
billion U.S. dollars) amounted to just one thirtieth of that of
the United States' and one ninth of Russia's.
</P>
<P>
The fact scuppers rumors that "China is working for arms
expansion" and that "China constitutes a threat", said Hu
Guangzheng, an associate professor of the PLA Academy of Military
Science.
</P>
<P>
"China has determined the size of its army according to defense
needs -- The PLA has always been a defensive army," he added.
</P>
<P>
Professor Qian Haihao of the academy said that while the size
of the army is reduced, high technology will be applied more
extensively so that the army will become more combat effective,
which is the trend of contemporary army construction.
</P>
<P>
The latest disarmament move will further improve the quality of
the Chinese army and shift the focus of army construction from
being labor intensive to being technology intensive.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has made great efforts to resettle
demobilized personnel, for the government officials consider that
the quality of what is done for the demobilized is a guarantee for
the success of the disarmament program.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that this year about 50,000 demobilized officers
are to be settled, while over the years an aggregate total of 3.1
million demobilized officers have been assisted by the government
with their re-entry into civilian life.
</P>
<P>
Demobilized personnel have been transferred to the fields of
land reclamation, railway construction, forestry, industry,
commerce and judicial departments. Records from the PLA General
Political Department show that 600,000 of the 3.1 million
demobilized officers have become highly-competent employees in
their civilian work units.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
