<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ``Chifeng Important for Study of Chinese Culture'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China's leading archaeologist
has called on specialists nationwide to pay more attention to the
area north of the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
"The ancient culture near Chifeng City and the cultures of the
Yellow River and the Yangtze River jointly gave birth to ancient
Chinese civilization," said Zhang Bozhao, curator of Beijing's Palace
Museum.
</P>
<P>
Zhang pointed out that the area near Chifeng, where farming and
nomadic cultures overlapped in ancient times, had a unique culture
as important as those in other places before the Xia Dynasty
(c.21st-c.16th century B.C.). And the culture there might
have spread to Siberia and Xinjiang, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Most historians have always believed that the central part of
China was the only birthplace of the Chinese people and culture.
</P>
<P>
Leading domestic and overseas historians and archaeologists
recently convened in Chifeng to discuss the ancient local culture.
</P>
<P>
They visited the Xiajiadian ruins, the ruins of post-Hongshan
Culture, the Jingong Palace ruins of the Liao Dynasty (907-1125)
and other cultural remains in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region
and Liaoning Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Goes Crazy for Electrical Appliances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Each year, about 7 million
Chinese get married, and most of them set about furnishing their
new rooms or flats with the essential electricals of life. At the
same time, 80 percent of existing families are just about ready to
replace this applicance or that which may have been bought in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that by year 2000, 3 million color TVs, 2.5 million
refrigerators and 3 million washing machines nationwide are
expected to be consigned to second-hand dealers and replaced by
new ones.
</P>
<P>
Liu Fuzhong, secretary-general of China Association of
Electrical Appliances, said that China now has 2,500 electrical
appliance manufacturers, churning out 120 different products.
</P>
<P>
"Production is on a huge scale," said Liu. China is now the
world's largest producer of color televisions, refrigerators,
washing machines, electric irons, fans and rice cookers. It also
produces about 20 percent of the world's air conditioners,
refrigerators and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
Chinese products are available in 173 countries and regions,
particularly the United States, Japan, Germany, France, UK and
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
High production strength has caused a fiercely-contested price
war to break out among producers. Compared with 1994 prices,
refrigerators, washing machines and air conditioners are half
their costs. Prices of color TVs and micro-wave ovens are down by
35 and 50 percent. VCDs in particular- production only began in
1995 - have witnessed a 16-fold sales increase as prices have
fallen by 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Price cutting, however, does not imply a market depression,
but a strategy of pursuing low-margin high-sales operations," said
Liu.
</P>
<P>
Rural China also promises to be a new market horizon. The
market is currently stagnated by low incomes of rural residents --
earning of China's 900 million rural people are 12 years behind
the level of urban folk. Right now, most rural residents have
little more than a small TV or radio. But things will certainly
change.
</P>
<P>
"As the rural economy develops, farmers in poorer provinces
will get richer while the more-remote villages will be linked to
grid supplies. Furnishing houses to levels of comfort and
convenience we expect these people will involve the sale
of some 168 million color TVs, 180 million refrigerators and 170
million washing machines," predicted Liu. These figures correspond
to 10, 14 and 16 years of national annual production at the
current level.
</P>
<P>
To tap this vast market of the near future, sector specialists
say that small, inefficient producers will be eliminated by fierce
price warring which will leave large, efficient operations in
control. These will advertise widely and accept low profit margins
on high turnovers. Their R&AMP;D departments will continue to develop
high-tech products with performance and quality to match foreign
manufacturers. And in that way the lion's share of the domestic
market looks set to stay with home producers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges Transparency in U.S., European Banking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai economic and financial
experts have called for transparency in U.S. and European banking
and hedge fund operations in the wake of newly exposed weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
"Transparency must be applied to U.S. banks and hedge funds as
well," Ekamol Kiriwat, former deputy governor of the Bank of
Thailand, said in remarks published Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since the financial crisis broke out in Thailand last year and
then spread to neighboring countries, Western policymakers have
laid blame on the lack of transparency in the Asian banking
system. Thailand and other Asian countries have been forced to
reform their financial sectors by imposing transparency rules.
</P>
<P>
But investors now are suspicious of hidden negative information
held by banks and hedge funds in Western countries, Ekamol was
quoted by the Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
After Alan Greenspan, chairman of the U.S. Federal Reserve,
organized a bailout of Long-Term Capital Management LP (LTCM),
attempting to avert damage to the U.S. economy, investors
suspected that there were other troubled hedge funds and their
collapse would spark a chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
The LTCM debacle had added momentum to the theory that hedge
funds are potential trouble. There is a call for transparency and
restriction of hedge funds, which play a significant role in
capital movement, especially in the short term.
</P>
<P>
Teerana Bhongmakapat, economics professor at Chulalongkorn
University in Thailand, said the LTCM bailout organized by
Greenspan demonstrated that the United States had recognized the
weakness in the U.S. financial system.
</P>
<P>
The hedge funds now pose a potential risk to the U.S. economy.
So far there is little information about their financial status
and how much they have borrowed, Teerana said.
</P>
<P>
Ekamol, however, added that this is a wrong time to apportion
blame. He said that as world financial leaders were meeting in
Washington, he hoped the G-7 and developing countries would make
joint efforts to solve the calamity.
</P>
<P>
Ekamol and Teerana shared the view that a world recession has
already begun and that world leaders must act to prevent the world
economy from plunging into a deeper recession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
