<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Stresses Ethnic Minority Group Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region has been successful in developing education in
its ethnic minority areas.
</P>
<P>
Part of this successes is due to the construction of nearly
5,000 schools buildings at a cost of more than 257 million yuan
(30 million U.S. dollars) over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi is a region inhabited by some 40 different ethnic
minority groups living mainly in the northwestern, southwestern
and southeastern parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
At present, all the region's ethnic minority villages have
primary schools and teaching stations available, even in remote
areas, and most of the towns where ethnic minority people live
have junior middle schools.
</P>
<P>
There are now 164 students in the ethnic minority primary
schools and 63 in the middle schools.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1980, the region has allocated more than 4 million
yuan annually to support primary and middle schools in 24 counties
inhabited by ethnic minority people, and secondary school
education in some nine other prefectures.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the region has established 120 special courses for
ethnic-minority girls, which has been a difficult educational
problem in the region.
</P>
<P>
The region also introduced special teaching methods for Zhuang,
the largest ethnic group in the region with a population of 15.18
million. One of these methods is offering courses taught in the
Zhuang language.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
