<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Almost three quarters of China's 900 million farmers have so
far singed new contracts with local governments to continue land
use for another 30 years.
</P>
<P>
China introduced the household contract responsibility system
and land contract system in the late 1970s and early 1980s, with
most farmers signing 15-year contracts with local governments.
</P>
<P>
-- A frontpage story said that the socialist market economic
structure has taken shape preliminarily in China. The public
ownership is the major part of the structure while the economy of
other forms of ownership is growing steadily.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin recently called on Party committees
and governments at all levels to give priority to agricultural
development and continue efforts to promote rural refrom in
accordance with a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, general secretary of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China and chairman of the Central Military
Commission, issued the call during his fact-finding tour of east
China's Anhui Province on September 25.
</P>
<P>
The most difficult task to reach the goals set at the 15th
Party Congress centers on sustaining stable agricultural and rural
economic development, said Jiang, noting that doing a good job in
rural areas will help to ensure overall smooth economic and social
development.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Despite lowered procurement prices and the natural disasters
which have plagued the area, the Xinjiang uygur Autonomous Region,
one of China's major cotton producers, had purchased more than
190,000 tons of cotton by September 25.
</P>
<P>
-- A series of activities, aimed at promoting public awareness
of the importance of energy conservation and environmental
protection, is being launched today across the nation.
</P>
<P>
These activities are particular this year as China is slowly
recovering from the severe blows given by this summer's
devastating floods.  
</P>
