<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, October 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece on Sunday urged leaders of the Yugoslav
Federation and ethnic Albanians in its province of Kosovo to begin
talks immediately.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the talks, as stated by Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki, is to
avert a possible military intervention by NATO. (Greece-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- A moderate earthquake measuring 4.9 on the Richter
scale hit Yugoslavia on Sunday, but caused no casualties or
serious damages.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian Seismology Bureau said the quake occurred at 13:19
p.m. local time and the epic center was in Kopaonik, some 180
kilometers south of Belgrade.  (Yugoslavia-Earthquake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said Sunday he
would not ease tight economic policies to secure political gains
in nationwide local elections this month.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said the cornerstone of the Greek government's policy
is to attain the entry into the European Economic and Monetary
Union (EMU) by the target date of January 1, 2001.
(Greece-PM-Talk)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- The Ugandan government condemned the Sudanese air
attack on Pakele trading center in the northwestern district of
Moyo district.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issed by the Ugandan Defense Ministry Sunday
evening, State Minister of Defense, Steven Kavuma, described the
act as an "act of aggression" which violates international law and
the principle of good neighborliness. (Uganda-Sudan-Air Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Defense Secretary George Robertson Sunday
dropped a strong hint that NATO may send troops to Kosovo to
enforce any political settlement of the worsening conflict.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC television interview early Sunday, Robertson
said: "It is conceivable that if (Yugoslav President) Slobodan
Milosevic is involved in a genuine ceasefire -- and not just some
cat-and-mouse tactic that he's been involved in before -- and
there is a prospect of a political settlement on the ground."
(NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
