<HEADLINE> Nigeria Held 0-0 By Burkina Faso at CAN Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria was held a goalless draw
by host Burkina Faso Sunday in Ouagadougou in a Group five
opening match of the 22nd African Nations Cup (CAN) slated for
Year 2000 in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The match in the Burkinabe capital is Nigeria's first
appearance at the continental event after being banned for two
and half years by the Confederation of African Football (CAF) for
withdrawing on the eve of the 20th CAN finals hosted by South
Africa in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The goalless draw is certainly a disappointment to the
Stallions of Burkina Faso who have been preparing hard for the
encounter, including an intensive training in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The Super Eagles of Nigeria, however, should be content with
the result, as the African football power is still recovering
from its disgraceful exit from the France 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Nigerian football observers said that Nigeria
would qualify for the finals after all, as none of the teams in
Group five, Burkina Faso, Senegal or Brundi would be strong eno
ugh to challenge the Super Eagles' dominance.
</P>
<P>
Super Eagles's chief-coach-to-be, Dutchman Thijs Libregts
flied to Ouagadougou with his team, but he had made it clear that
he would interfere with coach Shuaibu Amodu.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria won the CAN twice in 1980 and 1994, while Burkina
Faso's best result was the fourth place in January 1998, when it
hosted the 21st CAN finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
