<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arsenal Blank Newcastle, Chelsea Hold Liverpool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Dutchman Dennis Bergkamp ended
his scoring drought of the season with two goals which helped
defending champions Arsenal blank Newcastle United 3-0 at home in
the English Premier League match on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The win moved Arsenal up to the third in the team standings at
13 points, one point behind Manchester United who have a game in
hand and beat bottom side Southampton 3-0 on Saturday, and seven
adrift of leaders Aston Villa, 2-1 winners over Coventry City.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's other game Chelsea's Italian striker Pierluigi
Casiraghi scored his first goal in English football but Jamie
Redknapp struck home a late free-kick to earn Liverpool a 1-1
draw at Anfield.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea and Liverpool both have 12 points.
</P>
<P>
At Highbury Bergkamp could have had a hat-trick but saw his
second penalty of the match spectacularly saved by Newcastle
goalkeeper Shay Given three minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
The Dutchman ended his 10-game drought in front of goal after
21 minutes. French strike partner Nicolas Anelka split the
Newcastle defense with a pass and Bergkamp fired low past Given.
</P>
<P>
Bergkamp returned the favor eight minutes later, breaking onto
Marc Overmars' hopeful hoof forward and squaring for Anelka to
sidefoot home with the Newcastle defense nowhere.
</P>
<P>
After 65 minutes Overmars earned a penalty after being brought
down by Newcastle's Greek defender Nikos Dabizas, who received a
second yellow card and was sent off. Bergkamp tucked away the
spotkick to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
With three minutes left Bergkamp was felled in the area by
Philippe Albert but his penalty kick was parried by Given, who
had made a string of fine saves to keep the score down.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle's defeat ended their run of three successive league
wins and completed a miserable week following their European Cup
Winners' Cup exit at Partizan Belgrade on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Van Gogh's Paintings on Show in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of
American art lovers will have a chance to view the brilliant color
paintings of Dutch Vincent Van Gogh as 72 of his masterpieces are
on show in U.S. capital Washington.
</P>
<P>
The art exhibition, at the National Gallery of Art, started
Sunday and will run to January 3, 1999. It was the first largest
Van Gogh exhibit outside The Netherlands and in the United States
in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The paintings from 1882 to 1890 include some of Van Gogh's
best known works, such as the "Yellow House" where he lived in
the southern French town of Arles, "The Harvest" and "The
Bedroom."
</P>
<P>
The field of wheat, the potatos, the parks, the boat and the
pair of shoes, all the paintings feature the real life of the
artist in his time, showing his love of life.
</P>
<P>
Born on March 30, 1853, in Zundert, a village in the southern
province of North Brabart, the Netherlands, Van Gogh began to work
at the age of 16. He worked for a French art dealers company, took
a job as an assistant teacher in England and later became a
clergyman at home and in abroad. His hard life supported his
works.
</P>
<P>
On the first-day show, hundreds of art lovers waited outside
the gallery for hours to have a first look.
</P>
<P>
The paintings are on loan from the Van Gogh Museum in
Amsterdam. The exhibit will move to the Los Angeles County Museum
of Art on January 17 till April 4, 1999, before returning to the
Amsterdam museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Knowledge Growth May Widen Gap Between Rich and Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The global explosion of
knowledge now underway may create a widening gap between the rich
and poor countries, according to a report released Sunday by the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth in global knowledge may lift hundreds of
millions of the world's poor out of poverty, or throw them further
and further behind the wealthy ones, the report said.
</P>
<P>
New communications technology and plummeting computing costs
would enable the poor to tap into a rapidly expanding global store
of knowledge, which is crucial to improving their health and
living standards, but the rapid growth of knowledge would also
make it possible that the poor would fall behind more rapidly than
ever before, noted the report entitled "Knowledge for
Development."
</P>
<P>
Developing countries "need not reinvent the wheel, or the
computer or treatment for malaria. Rather than re-create existing
knowledge, poorer countries have the option of acquiring and
adapting knowledge already available in richer countries," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"In our enthusiasm for the Information Super Highway we must
not forget the villages and slums without telephones,electricity
or safe water, the primary schools without pencils, paper or
books," World Bank President James Wolfensohn writes in the
foreword to the report.
</P>
<P>
Low national incomes are not the only reason why poor countries
are less prosperous than richer ones, the report said. Many
developing countries lack the capability to acquire and adapt the
economic, technical, and social knowledge that has spurred many of
the world's development success stories.
</P>
<P>
The bank's chief economist, Joseph Stiglitz, said:"Knowledge
is one area where government policies can make a difference when
resources are scarce."
</P>
<P>
Many of the estimated 2 million children around the world who
die from diarrhea could be saved if their parents knew how to
prepare a simple solution of water, sugar and salt, Stiglitz
noted.
</P>
<P>
Carl Dahlman, main author of the report, believes that
governments that adopt policies to make the most of knowledge will
have major advantage in improving the lives of their citizens.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, developing countries are badly in need
of how-to knowledge such as nutrition, birth control, engineering
and accounting, and knowledge about attributes or characteristics
such as product standards, accounting systems or creditworthiness
of a firm.
</P>
<P>
The report argues that lacking knowledge is "information
problems" which in turn could lead to market failures such as
lenders' refusal to offer loans to poor people, because of the
difficulty in assessing their ability to repay.
</P>
<P>
It believes that knowledge gaps could be narrowed through
education, better phone systems and openness to exchanges with
foreign countries, including trade.
</P>
<P>
Founded 54 years ago, the World Bank is striving to become a
clearing house for all the development knowledge. It expects to
have its knowledge management system online by 2000 so that
clients, partners and member governments around the world can
benefit from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Ready to Mediate Between Turkey, Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi on Sunday announced Tehran's readiness to mediate
between Turkey and Syria to solve their disputes.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the announcement in a telephone conversation with
his Syrian counterpart Farouq al-Sharaa, the official news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Israel's conspiracy is the main target behind recent tension
between Turkey and Syria, Kharrazi told Sharaa. Tel Aviv is trying
to seize an opportunity in order to make the region insecure, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern over the recent developments between Turkey
and Syria, he underlined that Ankara needs to further preserve
self-restraint because military threats will not solve anything.
</P>
<P>
If there are any problems between the regional countries, it
should be resolved through negotiations and through the mediation
of other regional nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa appreciated the Iranian initiative aimed at eliminating
tensions between Damascus and Ankara, saying that his country
welcomes any endeavors by Iran in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Syria is not for any military conflict with Turkey, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Syria and Turkey were deteriorated in recent
weeks after Ankara reportedly massed up troops along its borders
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Turkey have been at loggerheads over issues of
separatist Kurds, water-sharing and the Turkish-Israeli
military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of backing the Turkish Kurdish
rebels, who have been fighting since 1984 for more autonomy of the
Kurds in southeastern Turkey and often launched across-border
attacks from their bases in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
And Syria has accused Turkey of forming military alliance with
Israel, saying that it threatens Arab security and undermines
Syria's bargaining position in peace talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Living in Iraq Kills Two Iraqi Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian living in Iraq
broke into a synagogue of Iraqi Jews Sunday morning and killed
four people, including two Jews,
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported the Iraqi
cabinet, under the chairmanship of President Saddam Hussein,
convened an urgent session on Sunday evening to discuss the
incident.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting condemned the killing, INA said, adding the
attacker, who was a holder of Egyptian passport and has been in
Iraq since 1991, was arrested by the police.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi security authority is looking into the motives
behind the assault, said INA. But it did not give further details.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish people now living in Iraq are numbered in
thousands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2115 GMT, October 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Sunday that there is a good chance for reaching an agreement with
the Palestinians and he is ready to pay the necessary political
price for it, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks after meeting with Hanan Porat,
head of the Knesset (Parliament) law committee, who briefed him
on the debate in the committee over a bill calling for
dissolution of the Knesset and early elections.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset has passed the bill in its preliminary reading
in late July, a day before the Knesset began its summer
recess. Three more readings are needed before the bill could
become law. (Israel-Netanyahu-Negotiations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu declared
Sunday that Israel is not to be involved in the dispute between
Turkey and Syria, saying Israel will "take steps" to reassure
Damascus about it, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement as tensions are mounting along the
Turkish-Syrian borders over Ankara's accusation that Damascus is
aiding Kurdish rebels in Turkey, an allegation which Syria denies.
</P>
<P>
The radio did not say what steps Netanyahu will take to
reassure that Israel will not be part of the dispute, but Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has ordered the Israeli army to
scale down its routine activities along the frontier with Syria to
signal Damascus of Israel's intention. (Israel-Turkey-Syria)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Visiting Egyptian President Hossni Mubarak said
Sunday that Egypt favors diplomatic efforts in solving the
Syrian-Turkish dispute.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak voiced the stand in talks with Syria President Hafez
Assad right after he arrived here in the morning on a one-day
visit, according to the Syrian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said the disputes between Syria and Turkey should be
solved through diplomatic methods instead of force.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will also travel on to Turkey Monday to try to head off
the potential military confrontation between the two countries.
(Syria-Egypt-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt, along with Israel with which it signed a peace
deal in 1979, will get less U.S. aid for the first time in almost
two decades, U.S. ambassador to Egypt Daniel Kurtzer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference Sunday with Zafer el Beshri,
Egypt's minister of state for planning and international
cooperation, Kurtzer said U.S. assistance to Egypt and Israel will
be "reduced by five percent since 1999."
</P>
<P>
However he denied that his country was planning a zero aid to
Egypt, the first Arab country to achieve peace with the Jewish
state under U.S. brokerage. The two have been awarded U.S.
economic and military aid as "peace dividends."
</P>
<P>
According to Kurtzer, the drop in the annual aid to Egypt from
815 million dollars to 775 million is a move the U.S. Congress is
undertaking in view of skinny U.S. budget resources.
</P>
<P>
The Congress has, however, approved to keep military aid to
Egypt intact. (Egypt-US-Aid Cut)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa reaffirmed
here Sunday the need to resolve the dispute with Turkey through
dialog rather than confrontation and threats.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Syrian and Egyptian newsmen following Sunday's talks
between visiting Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and his Syrian
counterpart Hafez al-Assad, Sharaa said that threats were
unacceptable and that the Arab stance was in support of Syria,
according to Syrian news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs, Sharaa added, are in favor of resolution of
outstanding issues between Turkey and Syria through cordial dialog
rather than any other means. (Syria-Egypt-Mediation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The Sudanese government has lodged a complaint with
U.N. Security Council against Uganda for its aggression against
Sudanese territory, and Eritrea for being an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press Sunday, Sudanese Undersecretary for
Foreign Affairs Hassan Abdin said Sudan has called upon the
Security Council to undertake its responsibility with regard to
this aggression which he described as flagrant violation of the
U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
He said that Sudan has officially informed the League of Arab
States about the motives and scale of the aggression which he said
constituted a violation of Sudan's sovereignty.
(Sudan-Uganda-Eritrea)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq on Sunday condemned the fresh Turkish invasion
of its northern territory, saying it violated the U.N. Charter and
principles of good neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency, the Foreign
Ministry said more than 10,000 Turkish troops invaded northern
Iraq on October 2 under the pretext of chasing elements of its
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Kurdish rebels have been fighting since 1984 for an
independent homeland in southeastern part of the country. They
found shelter in northern Iraq after Baghdad was rendered
ineffective in its control over there. (Iraq-Turkey-Condemnation)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981005.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latvians Vote for Easier Citizenship for Ethnic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Latvians have voted for easier
citizenship for ethnic Russians, preliminary reports from the
Baltic country's Saturday referendum show.
</P>
<P>
In a national referendum held in conjunction with the
parliamentary elections, 53 percent voted for the citizenship
amendments approved by the parliament, the Saeima, on June 22, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The June amendments nullified the existing provisions on "the
naturalization of aliens", and gave citizenship to children born
after the country's 1991 independences.
</P>
<P>
Latvian language proficiency tests would also be simplified for
applicants of non-Latvian ethnics older than 65.
</P>
<P>
The original citizenship law has been strongly objected by
ethnic Russians, which account for one third of the Latvian
population, and criticized by Russia, the United States and the
European countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
